        "id": "barty-chunk-0",
        "text": "and the Fabulous Fraud\r\r\rCory Allen Gilford\n\nCHAPTER ONE\rSong for the City, No. 12.\r      In the City, a house emanates music both day and night. Most never hear it. How could they? The song has played longer than most of the citizens have been alive. Some do hear the music, but all who have ears to hear wish they had not. Through its beautiful hum, it resonates doom in the hearts of its hearers. If ever you hear the chords, cover your ears. Only dread comes from those notes.\r      They drift from a record player, set upon a well-used chair. Perched on the rooftop, above majestic oaks lining the street below, it watches the city. No power cable feeds it life. Though it bears marks of age, its tune sounds new. Through wind, rain, sun, and frost, it plays on, masking itself in monotony and consistency. The spinning label reads �Song for the City, No. 12.�\r      The house has stood long before even the oldest city residents. Like the song, one could walk past the beautiful white columns, the trim and molding, the tediously carved decor and gold accents, and the tiger statue that guards the front garden, and disregard its ominous presence. Though the house is beautiful, its beauty could never mask the silent threat it impresses on its viewers. The sign on the front gate reads, �You are welcome here,� but the spear heads on the fence utter something entirely different: �You will die here.�\r      Should you miss the warning given by the bars, the main door has another message shrouded in beauty. In the middle of the tall, black wood, an inscription carved on a gold placard reads, �Many come to stay, few ever leave.��\r      It was to this door that the mail carrier walked, drawn by the familiar, yet forgotten, song. And when he finally heard it, he wished at once that he had not.�\r      He did not intend, that day, to stop at number 6067. He could not, in truth, recall ever seeing the house before. Sitting in his government-issued mail-truck, he studied the bars, the columns, and the tiger. He felt a powerful desire to look away but could not. He, at once, felt bathed in dread and curiosity. Where had this house been all the months that he worked this route?\r      The reasonable part of his brain thought, I can�t notice every house. That voice wavered, unsure of itself. Something about the house disquieted his soul. It knows.\r      His inner voice questioned. I must have dropped off mail here before. Maybe. He searched the front porch. Maybe I should knock.\r      He killed his truck�s ignition, and the engine slowed to silence.\r      No� Why would they be expecting me? I�ve never seen this house before. I�ve never met these people. He glanced at the tiger, which looked ready to pounce on its prey.\r      She looks precious!\r      The tiger did not, in fact, look precious. Becoming ever lost in his stupor, he had convinced himself that she was lovely. The claws�perfect for scratching his back. The eyes had no pupils, but they looked like they were longing for long walks on the beach. Of course, none of this made sense.\r      He stepped out of the truck onto the sidewalk in front of the house. When he stood straight, he appeared lanky and too tall to drive the vehicle from which he emerged. His clothes looked a size too small, but only because the correct size did not exist.\r      You know, I should meet these lovely people!�I am their mailman, after all. It�s my duty to get to know the people I serve.\r      And with this small consideration, Frederick the mailman swung open the black gate that read �you are welcome here.� He walked, sure that he was, indeed, welcome there.\r      He straightened his collar and brushed his shorts. His hand rubbed his bald head, brushing back imaginary hair. He resembled someone preparing for a job interview.\r      He walked the broken concrete path that led to the stairs of the stoop, each step burdened with anxiety. Yet, he could not help himself. He looked to his left and met eyes with an elderly woman watering the lawn next door. She stared only a moment before snapping her head to look away. Maybe she wanted to avoid seeing what would inevitably happen. I�m being paranoid.\r      But why should he not turn around and march back to the truck? Why not leave this residence alone and continue his route? Did he really have a reason to knock on their door? Would this unplanned visit bother them?�\r      I�m just going to head out, he thought, resolving to abandon his congeniality. This seemed right.\r      But something also seemed wrong. He had made up his mind, but his feet would not obey. They continued marching onward, resolute in their goal. He tried to look down at his feet, but his head remained locked, fixed on the door. As one trapped in a dream, Frederick spectated someone else�s perspective in his own body. \r      His fear surged. He could think only of a few conditions that might cause a lack of control in his limbs: a stroke, an aneurism, or a� a dream. The mail carrier must have been experiencing some sort of psychotic episode. This option, however unpleasant, brought some reassurance. Something natural seemed better than something supernatural, for an evil presence hung in the air.\r      He had to do something�anything. The woman, he thought. She could help.\r      His legs ceased their movement. He prayed desperately that this happened due to his own will. His head slowly swiveled to his left. He could see the lady, still watering her lawn. He tried to talk, but his lips failed to form the words. In his mind, he began repeating, Help! Please help me! Hello! God! Help me, please! He hoped thinking these words would make the sound come out of his mouth. They did not.\r      Instead, his body stood, staring at the woman. When she could ignore him no longer, she turned to address him. With a tone of polite confusion, she bellowed, �Hey, hon. You need something?�\r      I need help. I can�t control my body. My arms� my legs� They aren�t working. Call someone. Please!�\r      Nothing. No words formed on his lips.\r       �Yes?� she called louder. �Can I help you with something?�\r      He had given her the creeps; he felt sure. Frederick, a stranger, stared at her in silence. He empathized with her plain discomfort.\r      He felt movement in his face, but not because he had wished for it. A smile formed, a dark, slow, sinister grin. Then, his mouth opened. Frederick heard words come out, but not words he commanded.\r      �Honey, If I were any better,� he said smoothly. �I�d be dead.��\r      That�s not right, he said in his mind. The lady smiled awkwardly, nodded, and returned to her work. His head slowly turned back to face the stoop and front porch. Then, his feet began walking again, Frederick a prisoner in his own body.\r      He made quick work of the stairs leading to the covered porch and front door. He pulled back on the knocker, quite unintentionally, and slammed it into the door. The force of the knocker resonated through the dark wood. The placard that read �Many come to stay, few ever leave.� now seemed to glow in the darkness of the porch.\r      The door opened on its own, the words of the sign shrinking into the wall of the entryway. A voice, echoing in the cold of the house, said, �Come in and close the door quickly.� The last thing Frederick wanted to do was enter this house. Still, he obeyed, blinded by eyes unaccustomed to the darkness engulfing him.\r      As his eyes adjusted, he could see that he walked a long, dark hallway. Caged wall lamps dimly lit aged stone brick walls with blue light. After a thousand steps, the hallway opened into a large, circular room, arranged like a small arena. In the middle of the room, a dark body of still water, as big as a home swimming pool, perfectly reflected light from the ceiling. The brick of the wall faded as it rose, becoming a night sky. A small model of the moon glowed, hovering thirty feet above the water.\r      On the other side of the pool, stairs led to an upper level that circled around the room. Ten grandiose looking chairs sat in two groups arranged equally on both sides of the upper ring. At the top of the stairs, a grand, unlit, fireplace served as a backdrop for a throne. Between each chair, torches hung on the wall, waiting to provide light should the room need use.\r      You belong to me now.\r      The words echoed in Fredericks mind.\r      In a flash, a large mirror appeared on the opposite end of the pool. In the golden frame, he saw himself drenched in sweat. Frederick blinked, and a dark shadow of a man grabbed his reflection and slowly slit its throat. Blood tricked out along his neck, covering his uniform. He watched as his doppelganger slowly fell from the frame and dropped into the water, creating ripples that distorted the moon�s mirrored image.\r      Frederick let out a scream, now fully in control of his head. He turned left and right, surveying the room in full panic. �Where are you?!�\r      �Shh,� a voice whispered behind him, breathing deep on his neck. It sounded hoarse, and low. �Don�t disturb the quiet.�\r      Frederick, now hyperventilating, shivering, �What did you do to me?�\r      The demonic figure circled Frederick�s frozen body to stare at him straight on. �Not a damn thing.� It lifted a cigarette and blew into it. The end glowed orange in obedience.\r      When the being moved, it seemed to float. The demon, for no other word seemed appropriate, appeared as a man hidden in shadow. Where skin should have reflected the moonlight, shadow covered his face. White light shone from where eyes should be. Smoke formed the shape of his head and drifted into the air. It carried a long cane with its right hand. A dark, silver snake twisted around the head of the cane and seemed to run across the demon�s hand seamlessly.\r      �Not yet.� He straightened the collar of a silky, all black suit. His hands shone like polished tungsten. �I apologize for the inconvenience, Frederick.� Upon hearing his name, the mail carrier�s heart skipped a beat.\r      �Would you like a drink?� the demon asked. �Some water, perhaps? No? I just want to make sure you�re alright. I�m afraid I�ll be detaining you indefinitely. I have some questions for you.�\r      �What questions?� Frederick asked, still very much afraid.\r      The demon began walking back and forth, as a man pacing in thought. �Questions that I suspect I already know the answers to.�\r      Frederick, completely awestruck, responded. �How do you know my name?�\r      The being paused its movements for a moment. �I know a lot of things. That�s hardly impressive, Freddy.� Fredericks name trailed off and echoed like a low moan. �Something�s been bothering me for a while. Something hasn�t been quite right. I�m a man that likes knowing what to expect, you see. Ten or so years ago, some interesting things started happening that, until lately, I haven�t been able to explain.�\r      The tone in which this demon spoke struck Frederick as curious and conversational, almost genuine. This smooth-talking voice sent shivers through the mail carrier. �I d-don�t understand. What does this have to do with me?�\r      �I think a lot, actually, dear friend,� the demon continued. �Listen, Freddy. I�ve got power. But I know what to do with it. Some people don�t. You can�t simply go about messing with powers they don�t understand, you understand. And I�ve got a talent for holding people accountable.�\r      �Talent?� Frederick�s questioning made the demon pause. It glared menacingly at the mail carrier. Suddenly, without warning, Frederick�s frozen body sprung to life. It dropped to the ground, stiff like a pencil, Frederick prose in submission. If not for his nose, his lips could kiss the ground.\r      The demon, hunched over to look down on the mail carrier, lifted the cigarette to the middle of its face, and breathed deep. As it exhaled, the smoke merely melted into the cloud around its face. �I think a bit highly of myself, Frederick. Now, get up. You�re embarrassing yourself.� This command lifted Frederick�s lifeless body into the air. It returned to its pencil-straight, locked position.\r      �Don�t waste my time, Freddy.� Frederick could only agree. One more wrong word could kill him. He resolved to say as little as possible.\r      �I�m not evil�I realize this is all a bit much for you�but believe me, good people have no reason to fear me. Bad people, however, very much do. This city belongs to me. I make sure that when people, man, woman, or creature break the rules�� He drew on the cigarette and blew a puff of smoke in Frederick�s face. �Justice.�\r      �You�re the devil then?�\r      The demon chuckled. �The devil? That�s cute. He�s around.� He knocked his cane against the stone floor. The knock reverberated against the walls.\r      �So that�s what this is? A prison?�\r      �You don�t get any more questions.� The demon vanished in a puff of smoke. When it appeared again, it stood on the opposite end of the pool where the mirror once had stood. Where it had gone, Frederick did not know.\r      The demon spoke, his voice elevated to make up for the distance. �Do you like swimming, Freddy?�\r      One at a time, three bodies slowly surfaced in the water, faces up. They each floated still, parallel to each other. A man, a woman, and a child.\r      Frederick�s face betrayed him again, horrified at the sight. The demon responded to this with a laugh that filled the room.\r      �Don�t be afraid, good man! They aren�t dead. Just stuck, you see.� He walked to where he could reach the floating man with his cane. He pushed the body and it bobbed, stiff like wood. �This is Charles Garrison. You might have heard of him. Very rich, very nice guy.�\r      Frederick had indeed heard of him. Only recently, this man from the city had disappeared. The people of the city held him in high esteem for his large donations to local human rights organizations. �What did he do to deserve this?� Frederick cried, holding back groans of fear.\r      �Great man, really. Very generous. Did you know that he killed his first wife twenty-two years ago? No one knew because she died of a heart attack.�\r      �Then how was it his fault?�\r      �She was healthy as a horse, idiot! There�s more than one way to kill a person. You can do it by stabbing. You can do it by poison. Or you can do it by magic.�\r      The words stunned Frederick, mentally of course. He could not move. To think that Mr. Garrison had some sort of magical ability felt unbelievable. �He was a magician?�\r      �No, Freddy. He was rich. His lover dabbled in black magic. Some very dark stuff.� He lifted the cane into the air and pushed the man, Mr. Garrison, down into the water again. The body did not resurface.\r      �Who is the woman?� Frederick shouted.\r      �The lover!� It struck her body with a circular whip of his cane. She vanished in a puff of smoke.\r      Frederick looked at the body of the young girl, still floating, moving up and down in reaction to the movement of the water. �What about her? What was her sin?�\r      The demon would have been smiling had it a mouth. �She�s my niece. She�s quite nasty actually, little gremlin.� He knelt to look at her. �Freddy, I won�t tell you what she�s capable of. You don�t want to know.�\r      Frederick pondered this information. Now, he knew why the demon had brought him to this place. Something from his past had punched him in his mind. He had tried to forget, but the memory banged like a drum in sync with his heartbeat. He struggled to focus on the being. Come on! I can get out of this! \r      The being walked on the water of the pool as a solid floor. He bent over and pushed the girl down deep. Frederick tightened the muscles in his head, attempting to make something happen. For a moment, the ominous shadow flickered. Still, he remained. The demon walked slowly on the water, ever closer to Frederick.\r      �Ten years ago, something disturbed the waters of this pool. I came across a bottle floating upon it. Where did this come from? I wondered. How did a bottle find its way into the Pool of Souls? The note inside gave no answer to my thoughts. Merely a pact between two friends, Bullet and Steamy. Very childish nicknames.�\r      Frederick knew the names. When he heard them, his lip quivered.\r      �Familiar? I suspect so, Steamy.� The demon stared intently into Frederick�s eyes. The lights of its face seemed to be shining into the dark places of Frederick�s mind.\r      �Then, only a week or so more, a baseball. Then a candy wrapper. Then, yet again, a rose. All of these items, seemingly unrelated, appeared in my pool. Over the next year, the items became more and more complex. A TV, a toaster, a poster�even a pile of laundry! Littering my beautiful water. This must be some sort of accident. Perhaps the universe is playing a cruel joke on me. No one litters my pool. No one can access this water without my permission. It was impossible! But then, it happened.�\r      �What happened?� Frederick asked, but he already knew the answer.\r      �A cat appeared in the water. A grey cat. It lay lifeless, though I knew the truth. Then, I knew something was going wrong. Someone was intentionally sending things into my pool. That person was experimenting�growing their skill. Learning. Until they could do what no one in this life should be able to do.�\r      Frederick panicked. �I want to go! I want to leave!� he shouted.\r      �You cannot leave! You belong to me.� Growing in size, the demon laughed maniacally. Frederick�s mind flashed to the mirror. At first, he thought it showed a vision, but now he understood the truth.\r      �Who are you?� questioned Frederick, with tears in his eyes.\r      �My name is Saul. I am the first of my line, chosen to protect this dominion, that of both the living and the dead.� The dark figure drew moved closer as he spoke. The cloud of smoke around his head grew, shrouding the room in darkness. His voice echoed in the cold air.\r      �I am the King of Souls. I am their master. If you don�t bow in this life, you will bow in the next! I am your last hope. Don�t lie to me. Tell me what you did!�\r      \r      Darkness.\r      The devil comes to play at night.\r      He snatches those within his sight.",
