        "text": "CHAPTER TWO\rThe Boy with Purple Sneakers\r      Barty Beauregard stuck out, even though he tried to blend in.\r      �Animals.� He said quietly. The other students on the bus yelled, cussed, swapped seats, and threw trash at each other. He clearly felt out of place among the other students, and they could see it. They acted their age, but Barty had the demeanor of a sixty year old man.\r      By thirteen, he had been through enough nonsense for one life. His dead mother had left him at the age of three. His father, wherever he had gone to these days, had to have Barty�s head examined when he started seeing ghosts. �Nonsense, boy,� the doctor told him. �It�s all in your head.�\r      �So is my brain,� replied Barty at ten years old. This did not amuse the man. Other kids picked on him. His relatives told him to be quiet. Dr. Wilson told him that �a strong delusion has taken hold of you,� Barty was done with nonsense.\r      �Is this seat taken?� A large, pimply boy with red curly hair asked, indicating the empty place next to Barty.\r      �Yes,� Barty responded coldly, knowing the question had been rhetorical.\r      The boy, heavily confused, glanced at the empty seat and back at Barty. Barty caught his eye with a stare that could scare a prosecutor. Don�t you dare.\r      The boy moved on.\r      Barty did not intend to be mean or aloof. He just preferred people at a distance.\r      �Thirty-two days and counting�� He scribbled a note in his notepad. \r      He had not spoken face to face with his father, Andrew Beauregard, for thirty-two days. Mr. Beauregard audited business books for a living. �It�s a bit like detective work,� he explained. Barty understood this to mean �incredibly dull.� Before departing, Mr. Beauregard promised the boy, �I�ll be back soon, Barty.� But after a while, when the calls stopped, Barty suspected the worst. Famous last words.\r      So, it pleased him when a girl met him in the Hell Hall, an abandoned corridor at Mont Linola Junior High, and asked him to help with a simple task: get Beau Adams expelled. This could provide a perfect distraction while he waited for his father to return.\r      �He hurt my brother,� she cried. And Barty believed it.\r      If you looked up �terrifying� in the dictionary, Beau�s baby picture would be listed. At fifteen, Beau towered over the other kids. Held back the year before, he had a temper as hot as a cast iron handle. He threw kids off their skateboards for sport. Legend had it, he cornered a boy, held him down, and pushed a pin into his shoulder. Then, he played a part in the school play�as the Great Wall of China.\r      Barty knew he could do something about this. Actually, he would let Beau do the work himself. If Beau got into a bad enough fight, it would certainly spell expulsion. He had already secured probation by locking a seventh-grader in a locker for a day. When the janitor found the boy, he had soiled pants and a smell that would last a week.\r      Yes, Barty knew that he could do the job. He had already outwitted quite a few foes in his short life. But for his plan to work, he needed someone to be the bait. Fortunately, he knew the perfect fool for the job.\r      Preston Farrell, a fourteen year old, made girls squirm. The first time he managed to kiss one, he told everybody she begged for it. After enough guys had harassed her, she produced a damaging recording: Preston hounding, nearly cornering, her for a kiss. The school quickly changed sides. There would be no sympathy if Preston got squished�the school would welcome it.\r   �Step one: start a rumor about Preston.� He smiled and marked the list he had started weeks prior. �Check.� \r   At a school like Mont Linola Junior High, words spread like the flu. Kids traded gossip like trading cards. �The fortune teller, Mad Addy, had it out for him. She�s the one that did it, my mom said.�\r   �Oh yeah? Well, if you need test answers, ask the new girl. She can get anything.� All of this, Barty suspected, was nonsense. Gluttony for gullibility made the perfect foundation for Barty�s scheme.\r    A few bathroom conversations, slipped notes, and message board threads had sealed Preston�s fate. He had six months to live. Even the teachers began to whisper when Preston came around. Of course, Preston denied it�until the special favors began. Kids let him cut in line. They gave him their unwanted desserts, and some bought him tickets to see the latest superhero flick. His tune started to change. �Yeah� I have so little left. I just hope the doctors can figure something out.� Yeah, Preston. Barty thought. I hope so, too.\r      Next, Barty spread the net to Kelly Prescott. She adored mocking him, and her four groupies made a great crowd. Barty suspected she paid them well to act like seals, always clapping and laughing.\r      �Barty Beauregard,� she once began. �You look so handsome in your perfect school uniform. Did mommy iron it this morning?�\r      The Preppy Pinks laughed. �Oh, good one!�\r      �My mom died when I was three,� he stated. �I iron my own clothes.�\r      �Aw, little Barty doesn�t have a mommy to iron his clothes,� she mocked.\r      Once again, the girls cheered stupidly. �Wow! No mom? What a loser!� Kelly loved attention. And he would make sure she got it.\r      Barty mused, thinking back to the day he managed to rope her in, picturing his vantage point.\r      �Why? Why would I do that?� Preston Farrell questioned, hands still holding his spaghetti noodles by the fork. Barty spied the conversation from two seats away, pretending to be writing in his notebook.\r      �Because she wants you. Everybody knows, too.�\r      Barty could hardly hear through the sound of chairs sliding on linoleum and kids exchanging jokes. But amongst the chaos, he knew better than to let his guard up. Never too careful, Barty, he had thought. He surveyed the cafeteria, accidentally meeting eyes with the new girl across the room. She quickly turned away. \r      �Who knows? Who says that?� Preston prodded, curiosity growing. Barty�s mind lingered on the smell of wheat rolls drifting through the cafeteria. Ugh�\r      A tray crashing against the table snapped him back into attention.\r      �She told her friends, �I want Preston Farrell to take me to the End of School Dance.� And I heard it from some dude in chemistry.�\r      Layers of separation, Barty said to himself. Never too close.\r      Preston looked like he had swallowed wrong. His spaghetti had begun to look more like stomach contents. He had minced his bread roll with his bare fingers.\r      �She wants me, you think?� He rubbed his chin, considering the proposition.\r      Barty�s eyebrows rose. Take the bait.\r      The nameless boy continued, �If I were you, I�d make my move soon. You know. And I know. Kelly won�t be single for long. This is a once in a lifetime opportunity.�\r      Barty glanced up at an adult watching them from across the room. He took a mental picture of the man, his wild grin and loud voice, annoying the teachers with whom he spoke. Too much attention, he thought, turning his thoughts back to his table. \r      Preston�s cheeks lifted into a silly grin. He clasped his hands behind his head and reclined his chair. �She wants me. Kelly Prescott. I really thought she might. Would hate to disappoint her.�\r      From his pocket, Preston supplied a pack of WinterEsque mints. �Always ready,� as his catchphrase went. He did this a lot. Preston had no clue his breath mints smelled like bad news. He strode confidently from one side of the cafeteria toward No Man�s Land for losers: the popular table. His shoes, purple basketball sneakers, clashed with his school uniform�just the way he liked them. The whole school noticed.\r      Barty heard the girls behind him whisper, �what is he doing? Preston Farrell� He looks like he�s going to talk to Kelly�� Oh, but he was. Exactly as Barty planned. He had money involved in that interaction. Taking the dying boy to the dance, she would become the ultimate attention queen. \r      Every eye turned to watch the exchange. Barty took this opportunity to slip a five-dollar bill under the food tray on the table. Then, he exited, sure of his success.\r\r      Barty jerked to the side as the bus ripped around a corner. His hand slipped on the page, leaving a long line of ink. He wrote a few more lines but eventually tore it out. He crumpled the paper into a ball. �Should have used a pencil,� he remarked to himself.\r      The boy from earlier leaned into Barty�s personal space, over his shoulder. �Did you hear? Preston Farrell asked Kelly Prescott to the dance.� He spoke through a mouth full of breakfast.\r      �Oh yeah? Did he?� Barty pulled back. \r      �Yeah. I can�t wait to see what happens when Beau finds out. They�re still talking, aren�t they?�\r      Barty felt his mouth turn up into a small smile. �Yes, they are.�\r      �Beau�s going to destroy him,� the boy said.\r      �God, I hope so.� The words fell out of Barty�s mouth, too soon to stop.\r      �What? What do you mean?� \r      Barty summoned a quick cover up. �I said �probably so.��\r      �Oh! I thought you were happy for a second.�\r      Barty indeed felt happy. Everything had gone according to plan. But if the school thought he enjoyed the physical assault of Preston Farrell, things could get messy. If the faculty found out he had orchestrated a fight between two boys, what would they do? Could he be expelled himself? \r      He pictured the man watching him in the cafeteria. And what about the new girl? Students gossiped about her uncanny ability to get information. Could she be a snare in his plan? She had watched him in the cafeteria. Probably just a fluke, he assured himself.\r      The school bus came to a stop, and the students scrambled. They twisted and shoved each other, competing to exit. Barty sat, waiting. Once the last students left, he gathered his things. As he neared the exit, the driver eyed him in the mirror.\r      �Any news, Barty?�\r      �Not yet. I�ll ask tonight.�\r      The driver frowned. �It won�t be long. I�m sure you�ll know more soon.�\r      Barty hoped so, but he did not say any more.\r      \r      As Barty made his way to the entrance, students hustled to exchange last minute news updates before starting their studies. �Beau is going to kill him!� said a girl in a green jacket.\r      �I heard Preston has two weeks to live,� said a boy with blonde hair that stood straight up. �She only said yes because she knows he�ll be dead anyway.� \r      A couple of twin girls held hands and walked past Barty to the cafeteria. He overheard them musing, �what are you wearing to the dance?�\r      �I�m wearing blue sequins and a glittery hair bow and a long baby blue scarf.�\r      �Gross!� The other laughed. �Me too!�\r      The school buzzed about the soon-coming summer break and end of term dance. Posters adorned the walls with the dance�s theme, Gettin� Outta Here. One of the students had illustrated the posters with a red convertible. Driving the convertible, a student that looked like a character from a sixties� high school flick gave a peace sign with his fingers. In the passenger seat, a girl in a floral dress held her hat from flying off as they drove into the sunset. The drama department had even constructed a life size paper-m�ch� vehicle that students took photos with.\r      Not for an instant had Barty considered going to the dance himself. He preferred the solitude of life-giving activities, such as building plastic brick figures or collecting Monster Runner cards. He had no time for school functions or after school activities. \r      His eyes focused on the poster. What an odd detail, Barty thought. In the background of the illustrated sheet, he noticed someone had drawn little ghost-like spirits circling the Sun. From a distance, it looked like a sunny haze.\r      Then, out of nowhere, a voice called, �Sup!� Barty jumped.\r      Her bleach blonde bangs covered her eyebrows. The way her voice sounded, bright and friendly, did not match her general aesthetic, dark lined makeup and bat earrings.\r      Barty glared at her for a moment, then awkwardly returned his eyes to the poster. Leave me alone. \r      �What do you think of the poster?� She examined the poster herself. Barty changed his face purposefully to evoke interest without speaking. She continued. �Do you like it? Do you talk?�\r      �Yes,� Barty spoke before moving on, leaving the girl behind. What an odd individual, he thought.\r      Throughout school periods, Barty listened for news of Beau�s retaliatory plans. He asked around at lunch and took bets on who would win the fight. Only during his seventh period gym class did he hear word on the next part of his scheme.\r      Coach Grant, a thin balding man in his twenties, gave instructions on the warmup routines. He looked out of sorts as a gym teacher, looking more like a former glee kid. The students groaned as he barked out orders in his high voice. �I don�t want to hear it! If you can�t do a few push-ups, how are you gonna handle working a nine-to-five for twenty years?�\r      One particularly clownish student remarked, �by sitting on our butts.� The class laughed, sparking Coach Grant�s dictatorial tendencies.\r      He whistled loudly and barked, �Five laps from everybody! Let�s go!� This drew continued cries from the students.\r      Barty trailed behind in the slow group. Several boys sprinted immediately, competing against an imaginary group of runners. As they lapped the walkers, they would yell �watch out!� or �slow traffic move right!� Barty thought extraordinarily little of show-offs.\r      Instead, he found himself fast-walking behind a couple of girls and a boy that looked like he did not get out much at all. The three joked about running and made comments about how much they wanted to nap. Then one of the girls remarked, �Yeah, so Beau is really mad about the whole Kelly situation.�\r      Barty�s ears perked up. �What Kelly situation?�\r      The other girl, Corey, chimed in. �Barty, you were there. I saw you. You know about what I�m talking about.� Barty flushed. People did pay attention at times, an uncomfortable reminder.\r      �In the cafeteria?� He tried to play it off.\r      �Yes, of course. With Preston.� The first girl, Nelly, continued through shallow breaths. �Well, I heard he called Kelly and they had a huge fight. I don�t know if they�re gonna keep talking.�\r      The boy cut in, �So she�s free then? Maybe I�ll��\r      �NO!� said the two girls.\r      �Oh, c�mon, guys,� he replied, laughing to himself. �That�s mean.�\r      Corey came to his defense, �Jackson, you�re too good for Kelly. It�s not a dig on you, trust us. She has major daddy issues.�\r      The first girl continued, �But Beau�s fuming. Someone overheard him yesterday in the bathroom crying. He was saying some pretty scary stuff.� Barty walked faster to catch up, suddenly very interested. He did not know Beau had feelings. \r      �What kind of stuff?� Barty asked.\r      �Violent. He might hurt Preston.�\r      Barty wanted to feel good about this news, but part of him felt bad about Beau�s crying. It made the monster seem human.\r      �Who�s that?� Jackson asked, looking at a runner in front of them. �She�s kind of cute from this angle.�\r      �Jackson!� Both of the girls reprimanded him.\r      Barty recognized the light blonde hair immediately, but now he saw thick black and white striped socks that she wore. They rose to the middle of her calves, oddly long for a sweltering summer day.\r      �You don�t want that,� Corey said. �I�ve heard weird things about her.�\r      �Be nice,� Michelle replied.\r      �I�m not being mean. I just heard she�s just� odd. Talks to herself a lot. She disappears at lunch sometimes, and no one knows where. Probably a witch. I heard the inside of her locker�s covered with dead bones.�\r      �Sounds like a normal girl,� Barty interjected. He did not want to admit that he too felt uneasy about her. \r      �Where did she come from?� Jackson asked.\r      �I think she�s a foster kid or something,� said Corey.\r      �I wonder if she has a date to the dance yet,� said Jackson. �Maybe, I�ll go get to know her.�\r      Barty thought the girl looked like she moonlighted as a crypt keeper. He suspected that Jackson would not interest her. His favorite interests included farts and the latest news in the world of fishing.\r      Barty could not help but prod him on. �Maybe you should. You�re probably just her type.�\r      In the locker room after P.E., Barty showered in a private stall. He relaxed after rinsing the sunscreen and sweat away. His clothes had begun sticking to his skin, so he had nearly raced to wash. Outside, the other boys whipped their towels and made lewd comments about the girls they would like to date. Barty had no interest in being friends with any of the other boys in his grade. Usually, he found them gross at best and Preston-ly at worst. He had tried tuning out their loud grunts and jeers.\r      But then, Barty heard the words he had been longing to hear. �Beau�s doing it today.�\r      �What? Doing what?� another boy asked, sounding desperate.\r      �Preston. He�s confronting him, and he�s super mad.�\r      �What�s he gonna do?�\r      �He�s gonna kill him, I think.� The boy solemnly spoke. �Or hurt him bad.�\r      Barty�s ears burned. Wherever this happened, he needed to be there.\r      �Oh, dang.� The second boy chuckled. �I�ve got to see it. I put twenty dollars on Beau.�\r      �Yeah, me too. I don�t know who would bet on Preston. Guys a fish. Sure, he can swim, but he�s got no meat.�\r      Barty did not care about this banter. He craved details. He deepened his voice and called out. �Where is this supposed to happen?�\r      The first boy responded, �uh, it�s happening right after school. I think somewhere close to the bus line.�\r      �Thanks.� Barty quickly finished, grabbed his things, and left. Checking his watch, he began walking faster. He brushed his hair with his hand, but it mattered little. He had medium length curly dark hair that only a few specialty products could tame.\r      He began down the Hell Hall. Most students believed a body had been found there and avoided the pathway. Barty believed this a myth. Still, He would not jeopardize a good shortcut by fact-checking urban legends.\r      He walked half the hall's length when a voice called out after him. �You�re a little stupid, huh?�\r      Barty stopped, dead in his tracks. He had hoped to meet someone here. He left bait, after all. He shot around and saw the new girl, dry and clean, as if she had not just been running. \r      Surprise, surprise. �I don�t know what you mean,� he replied coolly.\r      She walked toward him, grinning. The faculty left the light off in this hallway. Only the red exit sign glowed in the dark. Her hair, illuminated by the light, almost resembled a devilish halo.\r      �I know about Laurie. And Kelly. And Preston. And Beau,� she teased. �You�re sneaky. But you should be more careful.�\r      Barty stood blank faced. He felt certain that he alone knew all of the details. He had not even told Laurie the whole plan. But here she stood, claiming to know everything. Barty knew better than to confess. �Ok, genius. Tell me what you know.�\r      She walked ever closer, one foot in front of the other. She carried the air of someone with power. From her pocket, she produced a single crumpled-up piece of paper. She tossed it with impeccable aim and hit Barty squarely on the forehead.\r      �You�re orchestrating Beau Adam�s demise. You started the rumor that Preston had cancer or something, because you knew Kelly would say yes when he asked her to the dance. You knew Beau couldn�t stand that. You�re planning on them getting into it and Beau annihilating Preston.�\r      He bent over and lift