id I wanted to go with you at all?� he said aloud.\r      The image cut to coach Grant, who appeared to be speaking on behalf of the school. He stood on the football field, talking into a microphone.\r      �It was my quick response that saved the day,� he leaned forward, peering at an imaginary foe. �Always watching. I never let my guard down. You never know when something might happen. When I saw what was going on up there, I immediately sent help.�\r      The journalist appeared on the screen again, behind a studio desk. �We spoke to Principal Green. He stated, �Mont Linola Junior High remains a stronghold of education. Your children will never be harmed in our care, we assure you.��\r      Sarah turned off the tv.\r      �Oh, my goodness.� Sighing, she sat down on the red couch Barty�s father had bought the previous summer. It still smelled new. �What a day, right?�\r      She offered him a bowl of ice cream, which he gratefully accepted.\r      �Sarah,� he said between bites of cookie dough. �Can I ask you something weird?�\r      She narrowed her eyes at him, trying to figure out the question before he asked.\r      �How weird?� Barty recognized this as an attempt to lighten the mood. He would not play along.\r      �Preston said something that bothered me. He said that my dad was�� He thought for a moment about what to say. �He said he was dead.�\r      Sarah continued eating her ice cream, looking at the television. Barty waited for a response, but she seemed locked into an imaginary program.\r      �Sarah? Did you hear me?� He surveyed her frozen face. Nothing seemed to be happening behind her eyes. Barty felt odd about this. \r      Then, she snapped back to life, like she had been processing the question. �What?�\r      Barty, startled, wondered what had been going on in her mind during that moment. Maybe she thought it, too.\r      �Yeah,� Barty tried to continue casually. �He said everyone thought I was in denial or something. Like I was delusional.�\r 