        "text": "CHAPTER THREE\rThe Lady in Blue\r      Twenty-five days before Beau cut Barty in the ear, Stan and Loyd Webster, attorneys for his dad�s work, walked through the front door of his house in historic Mont Linola. He understood historic to mean �old.� The house looked like a cottage, with thick wooden plank siding and a small front porch. On their quiet street, their large red convertible stuck out like a pimple, ready to pop.\r      When Sarah opened the door for them, their footsteps resonated on the raised floor. He could hear them enter all the way in his back bedroom. \r      �Barty, we don�t know how to tell you this,� Frank had said. He sat at their table in the dining room.\r      �Your dad�s missing,� Loyd finished, still standing, ready to leave. Apparently, they did know how to say it. Barty hoped he would never have to see them again, wearing their matching grey suits and big red glasses. They told him that the company would continue to pay Sarah for the time being.\r      Barty�s dad may have gone missing, but could he really be dead? At the very least, Barty hoped not. What would he do if both of his parents died?\r      The Saturday morning after the fight on the bleachers, when he woke, the day welcomed him with glorious, glowing light that filtered through the leaves of his shaded street. After a good rain, the vegetation seemed to glow with life. The greens almost looked blue, and the air felt cool and clear. He could hear birds chirping, beckoning him to come out and play. After eating a bowl of cinnamon and sugar cereal, he changed into the clothes that he had prepared and ran out the back door.\r      He carefully stepped on landscape stones that led to the back corner of his yard. If he missed, he knew his feet would step into the grass and sink into the mud, filling his shoes with moisture. He prayed to avoid this.\r      Then, when he reached the double doors of the white shed, one side green with pollen and algae, he threw them open and searched in the dark for his bike. An old musty smell hit his nose, but he did not mind it. He knew the smell from the many times he opened the shed, full of old gas cans, rusted screws, leftover paint, and lawn gear. Amid all the junk, he spotted the red, glowing shine of his bike.\r      He smiled. Time for a ride.\r      He had to work it out of the shed, lifting the handle of the lawn mower to free his bike�s handlebars. A plank of wood also crossed its path, so he threw that to the back of the shed. When he had it free, he left the shed open and guided it through the side corridor of the house that led to the front driveway. Here, he could feel his shoes squeaking in the soggy, freshly rained-on grass. \r      He opened the wooden fence gate that blocked his exit and crossed into his own fantasy land of open road. Before him, an empty street, nothing but houses watching him. Even the houses had yards between them with nothing but sparse oak trees. The air felt cool, and he knew he needed to be fast to enjoy the atmosphere. If he took too long, the sun would catch up to him.\r      The best part about Winsor St., at least in his opinion, was the portal to another world at the end of the road. Even though the sign at the street�s entrance read �Dead End,� Barty knew the truth. If one ventured past the limits of the paved road, through a dip in an empty ditch that crossed through some trees, that person would find another road. This road had been built specifically with thirteen-year-old boys in mind.\r      Once upon a time, before Barty had even been dreamt of, a railroad ran straight through the heart of St. Fischer Parish. This railroad connected the towns of Doverton, Eulina Springs, Mont Linola, LaFreaux, and Gardsdell from West to East. Today, one might never know this, save for the fact that instead of a railroad, a bike path had been paved over it.\r      Thirty-one miles of clean asphalt stretched the Parish from city to city. The Trail had a few rules posted on signs all throughout. The two biggest rules: No motorized vehicles allowed and Trail open from sun up to sun down. Using the Trail, anyone on foot or on wheels could travel all throughout the area. Sometimes, he would ride through great woods, whose trees grew a hundred feet tall. Other times, he would find himself on a bridge over murky, brown and green water, wondering what people or mysteries had been lost to the water long ago. On this Saturday, he only wanted to lose his worries, riding his bike so swiftly they could not keep up.\r      He carefully drove his bike through the dipping path at the end of his street and up onto the paved Trail. He looked left and right, careful not to interrupt a fellow bikers� speedy pace. The Trail looked as if it went on forever in both directions, a tunnel of trees and asphalt. He directed his bike to the left and took off, the trees zipping past him as he picked up speed. Occasionally, he liked to veer off the asphalt onto the horse trails that bordered the bike path. But on this day, he just waved at the people that used them as he sped past.\r      A quarter of a mile flew by, and Barty stood on his pedals to gain more speed. Ahead lay a tunnel that dove beneath a highway that crossed the Trail. He knew that, if he could gain enough momentum on the downhill side, he could come up without pedaling at all. A win, he thought.\r      He pedaled faster, his hair flying back in the wind. The air hitting his face felt colder as he picked up speed. Go, go, go! He thought as he entered the declining ramp to the tunnel. He pushed his bike with all of his might. The tunnel sat at the bottom, a hundred feet ahead.\r      Green bars flanked the sides of the ramp, blurring as he rode. Soon, they gave way to white walls. Then, he hit the smooth concrete floor of the tunnel, the sound of traffic reverberating in the air. The walls had been graffitied and the tunnel felt dark in the middle. He relaxed at the bottom and rode the momentum like a wave. \r      Soon, the incline hit his front wheels. Here waited the true test of his power. He estimated that he must have been flying at twenty-five miles-per-hour. Would his bike make it up the ramp without more pedaling? \r      He rose, still maintaining speed. Then, he noticed the bike begin to slow, his surroundings changing to green bars again. Come on, we can make it! But he could tell, half-way up the tunnel, that it would barely reach the end. He gave a few lighthearted turns with his feet, too tired to put more energy into movement. Then, reaching the top, he coasted forward into another tunnel of trees, leaving the road, with its noisy traffic screaming, behind him. \r      The narrow asphalt curved to the left so tightly, Barty could only see about fifty feet of what lay before him. He hugged the right side of the path tightly incase another biker should meet him head on. On the other side, he came to an intersection where regular street met the Trail. Then, he exited the trail to Mont Linola�s Lakefront area.\r      The Lakefront town area felt like a step back in time. Shops and historic houses lined a near perfect gridwork of streets, massive Live Oak trees forming glorious tunnels above them. Broken sidewalks framed the roads, giving walkers the opportunity to explore. Barty loved this area because he could stop in the local antique shop owned by Mrs. Susan Jennings.\r      The shop appeared more like an old house whose owner could not get rid of any of their possessions. On the outside, broken remnants of houses, vintage doors and shutters, leaned against the white siding. The front landscape had been filled with little ceramic statues of birds, blue, green, and red. A tiny gnome sat by the birdbath in the middle. \r      On the front porch, old signs from different beverage companies had been stuck to the walls. A few bench seats and a porch swing occupied the porch to welcome visitors to enjoy the view. Susan had the door propped open, inviting the cool summer breeze into the stale air of her shop.\r      As Barty climbed the familiar stoop, the smell of old fabric, rust, and mothballs filled his nose. He walked into the front room of the shop, Susan sitting behind the counter on his left. �Hello, again, Barty.� \r      �Hello.�\r      He nodded at her and looked around the room. He did not see anything new, necessarily, but he walked slowly, ritually, taking in the sight of items from the past. He connected with these in an unexplainable way. They soothed his mind, beckoning him to live in a simpler time.\r      As he walked through the rooms, his fingers brushed cold silver on a timeless coffee set. They looked plucked out of an old movie. He unconsciously rolled a wooden car, hand painted and lacquered by someone long gone.\r      The owner had converted a house into a shop. Each room had remnants of someone else�s life lingering like aftereffects of another time. In the back room joined to the entrance, the corner still had cabinets and kitchen features. The back door led to more outdoor artifacts from homes that had either been demolished or remodeled, leaving their bones for another to dig up.\r      Barty walked carefully through each room, trying not to bump into anything. Susan had stacked thin shelves on tables to hold decor, watches, spoons, play jewelry, and cups. He turned into the hallway that connected the kitchen to the bedrooms. Each of these had also been converted into housing spaces for ancient artifacts. The furthest room to the right held coats and dresses and jewelry that reminded him of an old movie.\r      There, a woman stood, her makeup done, wearing a blue floral nightgown that looked aged by time. She herself wore time like a jacket, having been touched by many years. Her wrinkles had crawled like tree roots across her cheeks and under her eyes. Her hair had turned grey.\r      Barty knew her from this exact room, for every time he visited, she lingered there looking at the clothing. Sometimes she stood by the coats, slowly fingering the details and lines. At other times, she sat in the rocker and watched the dazzling dresses swing against the white door where they hung, as each visitor pushed it open to look.\r      Barty stepped cautiously into the room where she stood, watching a blue, sequin dress, for what seemed to be the seventh time that Barty could think of. She muttered under her breath. He could not hear the words, but he could see her thin, lined lips moving. \r      He glanced out the window, feeling awkward. Then he turned to where she stood. The first time he met her, he knew instinctively that something had been off. He had grown used to them, their faint translucency, their muttering and moaning. He could tell their movement made no ripple in space, like the air itself did not recognize them. He had grown so accustomed to real people, he knew the fake instantly.\r      He did not dare ask Mrs. Jennings about her. He already knew what she would say. �Barty, who�s back there? Oh? You scared me. I thought I must have missed someone. Don�t play tricks on me, young man.� No, he had been there too many times before. He knew how it felt when no one believed him.\r      Usually, he would ignore them. Usually, he would avoid their eyes and try to walk away. He did not fear them. They were� him. A figment of his imagination or a part of his brain losing itself. He knew this to be true. But today, he could not help himself.\r      He knew the what. They were hallucinations. But why did they do what they did? Even if they came from his mind, which they did, they operated independently of his will. They had minds of their own. They went where they wanted to and said what they wanted. They even gave him information that he never learned for himself.\r      So, Barty watched her, muttering and frozen, wearing her old nightgown. Her skin was covered in sunspots and bruises, the way elderly people often looked. Her face had thinned into nothing but skin and bones, her grey hair falling on her shoulders, uncut.\r      He moved closer to her, hoping to get a glimpse of what she spoke. Then, quieting his breath, he heard her muttering, �the boy, the boy. What does he want? He listens. He watches.�\r      Barty froze, thinking he had intruded on her space. He stood back, slowly. Then, he reminded himself, she�s not real. He reversed course, walking clearly to her side.\r      Then, she whipped her head to glare at him. Her swift movement had stunned the boy. Her eyes had grown wide and threatening. �What are you looking at?� she demanded, her voice harsh and croaky.\r      �I� why are you here?� He swallowed his fear, his heart racing. �I mean, why are you always here? Every time I come here. You�re here. In this room.�\r      She looked forward at the dress and ran her fingers over the sequins. They did not move when she touched them. Then, softly, she spoke under her breath. �Why should I leave? It�s mine. It�s mine. It�s�� then, as if a brilliant idea had struck her, she smiled brightly and looked at Barty with excitement. �I used to be a dancer, you know.� She turned to look at the dress, her eyes beginning to water.\r      �That�s very cool.� Barty did not know what to do with this information. �Do you like the dress?�\r      She tried to grab it. Her fingers sank through the fabric like a hologram. �It�s mine.�\r      Barty studied the dress. Did one argue with imaginary figures?\r      �Do you ever think about leaving?� Barty asked. \r      �Why would I leave?� She responded. Her voice had a hint of bitterness.\r      �I don�t know. To explore or to see things.� He wondered whether his imaginary friends could go elsewhere at all. What would happen if they tried?\r      �I seen things, boy,� she said, sounding insulted. �I seen the city, the lake, the country. Danced with the governor. I loved. I�� she stopped mid-sentence.\r      �You what?�\r      Her face changed from stern concentration to a look of fascination.\r      �I was a dancer, you know.�\r      Barty knew. \r      �You said that already.�\r      Her face flushed pink momentarily, a rare color that stood out on her white face. �I did? Oh.� She looked into the dress as one would a window, dreaming.\r      Like a lucid dream, Barty had a moment of curiosity. He wanted to prod, to find out what these specters could tell him.\r      �What is your name?� he asked, hoping that this would not offend her.\r      Her lips curled into a soft smile, and she thought. �Florence.�\r      �My name is Barty.�\r      She turned to look at him fully, perhaps for the first time. �Thank you, Barney. I- I,� she stuttered. �I was a dancer, you know.� Then, as if he had disappeared himself, she turned back to the dress, stroking it softly. \r      Barty left her there in the room, continuing to mutter.\r      �Did you find anything interesting today?� asked Mrs. Jennings, looking up from her book.\r      Barty walked to the glass countertop, slowly and carefully. �Mrs. Susan, do you believe in ghosts?�\r      She closed the book and placed it on the counter. �I, uh, I don�t know. Maybe. Why do you ask?�\r      He thought at this moment whether to say something about the old woman in the back room. �Just wondering,� he said, smiling darkly. �You�ve got a lot of old stuff here. Some people say ghosts cling on to their old stuff.�\r      She smiled over her glasses, resembling a cat. �Oh, Barty, then I think I must be in trouble.�\r      With perfect timing, a knocking noise came from the back room. They both looked up, frightened for a moment.\r      Mrs. Jennings spoke again, sounding like she had swallowed a toad. �That�s probably just Fiskers.� Barty understood Fiskers to mean her orange tabby cat that seldom walked around the store. �There�s a woman there on Dapier Street,� she began again. �She does fortune telling, or cards, or something of the sort. But I never mess with that stuff, myself. I�m Presbyterian.�\r      Barty felt a surge of mischief. �There�s ghosts in the Bible, Mrs. Jennings.�\r      She froze, eyes locked on his face. �Oh? That�s,� she said before swallowing, �interesting. I�ll have to look into it.�\r      Barty�s eyes wandered around the room. �I�m sure it�s just exaggerated, of course. Or,� he paused and looked at her again. �I hope.�\r      He had clearly stunned her. Whether or not she enjoyed this, he could not tell. He felt a certain satisfaction when playing with superstitious people. �I�ll see you late, Miss Susan.�\r      �I, uh, okay. I�ll see you later, Barty. Very nice seeing you.�\r      As Barty walked out the door, he caught a glimpse of her hands shaking. She looked toward the back room, clearly moved by the sound. He walked down the steps to his bike, feeling quite sure that the sound had indeed come from Fiskers.\r      He biked the few blocks that led to the Lakefront, perhaps the best part of Mont Linola. A three mile stretch of neatly kept green grass and ancient oak trees lined the shore of Lake Phillipas. Lake Phillipas itself dwarfed the town of Mont Linola by its ocean-like appearance. Indeed, all the towns along the Trail ran along its shore. To the naked eye, it appeared infinitely vast.\r      Barty knew better. On this day, when the rain had just cleaned the atmosphere, one could pear across the lake and see the outline of the large buildings of the City. From the Lakefront shore, he could see the causeway bridge that stretched twenty-six miles from Mont Linola to the other shore. Cars crossed back and forth creating an infinite loop of traffic noise that filled the air.\r      Barty sat on the concrete wall that separated the grass from the dark and cloudy water. He watched the City, sitting there on the skyline. He remembered a trip he once took there and smiled. He had met eyes with a panhandler. He felt frightened by the man. But suddenly, the person shifted shapes into a horrible floating specter, and Barty laughed. Something about the image had brought him peace.\r      �Good show!� He remarked, throwing the figure a dollar.\r      Thinking about this, Barty listened to a new noise. Slow, creeping footsteps crushed grass behind him. Before he could react, hands crashed into his back, forcing him over the edge, into the water.\r      He caught himself as he landed in the knee-deep shallow bank. His sneakers sunk into the soggy sand under the water. Voices cackled behind him, the unmistakable laughter of Beau Adams and Preston Farrell. \r      Barty whipped around, furious. �What the hell!� he shouted at them, standing over the wall. From the ledge, they stood at least seven feet above him.\r      �How�s the water, Barty?� Preston shouted, sitting on the edge. He set a large, half eaten, sandwich down on the wall.\r      In their normal clothes, they somehow appeared dumber than they did at school. Preston wore a tan, athletic tank top, aviator sunglasses, and black athletic shorts. Barty could not see, but he felt certain that the boy�s purple shoes hid behind the concrete ledge.\r      Beau wore reflective, fishing sunglasses. He had an oversized energy drink tee-shirt and khaki cargo shorts. Unfortunately, he fulfilled Barty�s every imagination of his out-of-school alter-ego.\r      Beau then lifted Barty�s bike and cast it over the edge. He made it look so easy, he could have been throwing a football.\r      �Why?!� Barty cried. He knew why. \r      �We thought you might like to bike to your dad,� Preston challenged. �Since he�s probably out there somewhere.� He took another bite of his sandwich, meat flapping out the sides as he set it down.\r      Beau laughed at this, another mark against him on Barty�s wrongs list. Barty attempted to calm himself but began dreaming up revenge schemes as he struggled to lift the bike out of the muck.\r      �No girlfriend to protect you?� Beau asked, clearly trying to say something clever. �Or, uh, boyfriend.�\r      �Shut up, Beau,� Barty shouted, unafraid of the consequences. He knew at the very least, the boys would not come after him while he stayed in the water.\r      Still, Beau ground his teeth, glaring at Barty. Barty imagined the strain he must feel having to think that hard. �Don�t give yourself an aneurysm,� Barty continued.\r      �You think I�m so dumb?� Beau shouted again. �I know you and Mildred did something.�\r      �So did your mom,� Barty�s tongue was moving faster than his brain now. �And look what happened.�\r      Preston chuckled at this, which infuriated Beau. Then, Preston got up and started playing with a bat that he had brought along, pretending to hit some imaginary ball.\r      �It�s easy to make mom jokes when your mom�s dead.� Beau muttered.\r      �No,� Barty started again. �It�s easy to hurt people when that�s the only thing you�re good at. It�s easy to shove people when they�re smaller than you. But you think that makes you tough. That makes you a coward. That makes you�� He stopped himself, afraid that he might literally push Beau over the edge. �Do you have anything else to say? Or do you want to kill me now?�\r      Preston swung the bat again. �You're lucky you�re still walking��\r      A small brown shadow cut him off, forcing the two bullies to jump back. There, where his sandwich rested on the ledge, hardly protected by parchment paper, a small bird had swooped down. Unafraid of the onlookers, it pecked at the seeds on the bread. Its bouncing brown body and speckled underside nearly matched the concrete wall�s color.\r      Preston glared at the bird, his fists gripping the bat. �You little�� He lifted the bat, posing for a swing.\r      Barty could not believe it. He did not want to think that even Preston could do such an awful act, but before he could react, the boy launched. The bird, noticing the movement, started to fly. The bat crashed into its tiny body, midair, sending the bird flapping into the water.\r      �You absolute�� Barty summoned the worst curse word he could think of. He lunged forward in the water to where the bird floated. The flapping wings slowed, struggling to reorient itself in the water. Then, it stopped altogether, Barty feeling helpless as he watched.\r      �If you and Mildred ever come around me again,� Beau said, �I�ll kill you. I swear to god.�\r      �He doesn�t mean that,� Preston interjected.\r      �Yes I do!� Beau replied, sounding hurt. �I�ll throw him off a cliff.� They began walking away, their voices trailing off. The last thing Barty heard was Preston remarking, �We don�t have cliffs.� He noted that Preston left the sandwich there, an eyesore on the wall.\r      Barty looked down at the helpless, dead bird, floating on the water. Something inside him burned. A feeling of rage, empathy, or sadness all combined. The creature had been helpless, small, weak. Preston, comparatively, had been a giant. He saw Gabe in the bird. Maybe even himself. No, I�m not helpless. \r      He never imagined touching a wild animal, certainly not a dead one. Compelled by emotion, he cupped his hands in the water under the bird and lifted it out of the water. It sunk into the skin of his hands as they rose. Barty grit his teeth, trying not to cry.\r      He could feel his palms heating with the anger that pulsed through his body. They started tingling as blood from the animal ran through his fingers. Why? Preston�s nothing but a worm. Nothing but a worm� \r      The bird twitched. Its leg strengthened, as it straightened its torso. Barty almost dropped it, shocked by the revival. Instead, he moved to the large concrete barrier that reach out into the water and set it down. Soon, the bird had completely woken and stood. It twisted its head and gratefully chirped at him.\r      Barty, stunned, waved at it. He shook his hands in the water to rinse the blood and watched as the bird flapped to rid itself of moisture. Then, as if nothing had happened, it flew to the wall and resumed pecking at the sandwich. This filled the boy with delight. Eat the sandwich, friend. \r      \r      Sarah nearly fainted when Barty entered his home, wet up to his thighs and covered in mud. She had been folding laundry in the front room. An episode of Dead Close, a reality show that paired romantic suitors with ghostly lovers, played on the living room television. Barty hated the show, with its over the top host, ranting and raving when mediums �connected� with lonely spirits. \r      �Beau Adams,� he responded in a lifeless tone.\r      �Beau Adams,� she repeated, thinking. �That�s the boy that cut your ear! I told you not to hang around him. No wonder you smell like a turd.�\r      �I didn�t hang around them. I didn�t look for them. They found me at the Lakefront.�\r      �Did you walk the other way? Did you call for help? Did someone see you? Did anyone offer to intervene?�\r      He wondered if mothers acted like this when their children came home hurt or bleeding. �I just wasn�t paying attention, and they pushed me.� He paused and bobbed his head, forming words. �Into the lake.�\r      �INTO THE LAKE?� She shrieked, suspiciously dramatic. �You hate being wet,� she argued. �And that�s assault.� She folded her arms and tapped her foot. Somewhere in the argument, the conversation shifted into silliness.\r      �It is assault. You�re right.� Barty replied flatly. �You call the police. I�m going to go take a nap.�\r      He walked to his room and gathered clothes to wear after showering. In the shower, as the dirt and grime slid down and swirled around the drain, he wished he could rinse off the frustration he felt. Beau said something that almost slipped by him. I know you and Mildred did something. But now, with nothing but his thoughts, he processed the information. What would happen if Beau and Preston told the principal their suspicion? What had Mildred done to them? What did they know?\r      One person brought more questions than answers. One person had shown up at just the right time and place. This person knew more than she should have. And, his brain buzzing with thoughts, Barty knew what to do. He needed to learn more about the new girl that had saved his life.",
