        "text": "CHAPTER FOUR\rThe Ghost in the Hall\r      On Monday morning, Sarah drove Barty to school, a gesture of kindness.\r      �Beau and Preston were expelled,� she informed him on the way. �Got the call yesterday.�\r      Barty smiled. At least his plan had worked. �What about the other boy?�\r      She did not know the answer to that.\r      When he arrived at school, the halls reverberated with gossip about the fight.\r      �Beau tried to kill Barty!� A boy with blonde hair that stood straight up said. �But Barty�s girlfriend, Kelly, protected him. They�ve been going out.� Barty rolled his eyes. He passed by a group of cheerleaders chatting outside their home room. Their eyes followed him as he walked, and they suddenly began whispering to each other. He could hear a boy telling an exaggerated version of the story to a small group of the chess team. �So, Barty pulled out his own knife! They dueled in knife to knife combat.� Nonsense, he thought.\r      �Barty, she�s coming for you.� Mildred�s voice whispered in his ear. But when Barty turned to see her, she had disappeared. Of course, he thought. Instead, amongst the crowd of students heading to classes and exchanging notes, he saw five pink bows bobbing on the sea of hairstyles. Kelly Prescott led her group of preppy pinks in his direction.\r      �BARTY BEAUREGARD!� She called out, the words ringing in his ears.\r      He turned to escape, but the wall of students blocking his path made it near impossible. In fact, students had begun gathering to watch when they heard his name in the air.\r      �Barty! What a surprise!� Kelly began. \r      �Surprise?� Barty questioned. �We see eachother everyday.�\r      She giggled with her band of Preppy Pinks, each nodding their agreement. �Well, I�m still happy to see you, Pookie.� She sounded almost giddy. \r      �Pookie? Okay.� Barty backed up as she moved closer to him, trapped by the group of gathered students. �What�s going on?�\r      �You must know by now, Barty dear.� She moved closer to him, innocently twisting her hair with her pointer finger. �Preston won�t be able to take me to the dance anymore. Beau is also out of the picture. I just figured, since we always flirt and tease��\r      �Flirt and tease?!� Barty cut in. Her perfume tickled his nose with lavender petals.\r      �Oh course. You don�t think I really hate you?� Her eyes had become huge and desperate, like a baby looking for attention. �The way I see it, it only makes sense.�\r      Barty felt he knew what came next. �I thought you never dreamed about going out with me? You want me to take you to the dance?�\r      She grinned. �Yes! Of course I�ll go with you!� She threw her arms around his neck.\r      �Kelly, I wasn�t asking you�� but it was too late. Kelly Prescott had already begun marching down the hallway. Everyone had seen the interaction. She had trapped Barty and he had nowhere to run.\r      �I�ll talk to you at lunch, Pookie!� Off she went. \r      Barty watched her leave, not out of romantic longing, but out of exhaustion. He scratched the back of his head, wondering what had happened.\r      Throughout his classes, students whispered his name. Teachers used him as their �volunteer.� In chemistry, he helped the teacher light her hands on fire with methane bubbles. The experiment backfired when his sleeve caught fire. In history, the teacher opined on whether or not Barty could be related to the famous Civil War general under the same surname. He hated this association. All the attention had started to get to him. When he crossed paths with Mildred between classes, he thought about her ability to vanish. He longed for her talent. Could she teach him a thing or two?\r      At lunch, Kelly cornered him again and forced him to sit with her. He felt compelled. But all the time, he watched for Mildred to show up, but she never appeared.\r      �So I�ll be wearing pink. You have to wear pink as well, Barty.� She did not stop talking the entire lunch period. She told him the flowers she wanted and the expensive rental store where he could get a pink tuxedo.\r      �Okay, yeah.� Barty half listened. He would run the moment he got the chance.\r      When he finally pulled away from Kelly, he went straight to the school counselor�s office. Barty would see the councilor as part of the principal�s plan for �establishing trust� with Barty and Mildred�s guardians.\r      As he arrived, Mildred exited the office.\r      �Barty!� Her eyes lit up when she saw him.\r      �Hello,� he responded, unsure what to say.\r      �Mr. Friend is nice. You�ll hate him.� \r      Barty blinked. �Mr. Friend? That has to be a joke.�\r      It was no joke. Mr. Friend stood in the open doorway, beaming down at the two of them.\r      �Oh! Sweet babies!� He had thick brown glasses, curly hair, and a tan sweater vest. �Come in, Mr. Beauregard! I�ve been looking forward to this all day!�\r      Mr. Friend had a flamboyant kindness that made the room feel electric. He had decorated his office with posters that read, �Happiness is a change of perspective,� or �You can succeed!�\r      Barty hated it.\r      �Take a seat. Take a seat.� He motioned to the big leather seat in front of his desk. He sat in the accompanying chair next to Barty.\r      �Barty, tell me about yourself!�\r      Barty did not know what to say. He did not enjoy speaking to strangers, especially when mandated by the school. Something also seemed familiar about this man, as if he had seen him somewhere before.\r      �I�m thirteen,� he began. \r      �I remember thirteen!� Mr. Friend somehow always sounded on the verge of tears. �What an exciting age! Tell me more.�\r      Barty felt uncomfortable at his enthusiasm for discussion. But he trucked on. By the end of their hour-long session, he had discussed his mother�s death, his missing father, his caretaker, and his fear of tightly enclosed spaces.\r      As they began to wrap up, Mr. Friend typed a few notes on his 