rt of psychotic episode. But this he would not do.\r      �Miss Gerard,� he used her last name. �I know that a girl died here a while ago. What happened?�\r      She frowned. This line of questioning disturbed her.\r      �It was before I worked here, Barty.�\r      Barty pressed further. �But have you heard about it?�\r      She stood up again, and walked to the cabinet. She pulled out some pain killers. �Does your head hurt?� Barty nodded agreement. He took the pills willingly.\r      Then, the nurse sighed.\r      �I heard about it. If I�m not mistaken, it happened by accident. She died in the school swimming pool. Some kids had pushed her in. It was some sort of horrible joke gone wrong.�\r      Barty felt that he had heard enough. This did not ease his discomfort. Someone had to be playing a prank on him using this old story. Did someone learn about his propensity to see people that did not exist?\r      The nurse told him that she would be contacting his guardian to let them know about the incident. He thanked her for her care and left, feeling worse than when he had gone in.\r      As he exited the doorway, Principal Green stopped him, wearing his navy blue, pinstripe suit and bow tie. He wore a variation of this outfit everyday. The students suspected that he mowed the grass and went to bed in a suit. \r      �Barty,� he said, placing his hands on Barty�s shoulders. This made Barty squirm slightly, uncomfortable with being touched. �Are you alright? I heard from the nurse that something had happened to you in the hallway.�\r      Barty, embarrassed that yet another person had heard of his fainting spell, attempted to sound put together. �I�m fine. I just needed to eat something.�\r      The principal eyed the boy, skeptical of his response. �What were you doing, hanging around the C Hall? Most students don�t go in there, I might add. We don�t even keep the lights on.�\r      The boy thought carefully about his response. He did not want to give Principal Gree