        "text": "OCTOBER 1st, 2000\rPOOL DROWNING AT MONT LINOLA JUNIOR HIGH LEAVES COMMUNITY IN SHOCK\r      Parents and students at Mount Linola Junior High School are mourning the loss of a beloved student, Melora Freedman, 14, after a tragic incident that happened Friday night. \r      Melora and five other students (un-named) went for a swim at the school swimming pool after midnight. Faculty seemed unaware of their plan to swim. We spoke to the principal, Mr. Gaylord, and he told us that swimming without permission is strictly forbidden, especially with no lifeguard on duty.\r�This is a tragic incident that never should have happened. The kids snuck into the pool, and they knew better,� said Mr. Gaylord.\r      Police are investigating the incident, but as of right now, they suspect no foul play.\r      Melora was beloved by all her teachers and fellow students. Her mother wants the public to know, �Please don�t let your kids do this. Watch your babies. She was a star. No mother should ever have to go through this.�\r- Frank Gritzer, THE TIMES OF ST. FISHER\n\nInitially, Barty hoped that the article could shed light on Laurie. Instead, Frank Gritzer of the Times of St. Fisher only mocked him. Not even a picture accompanied the record with which Barty could compare to Laurie. Now, Barty had more questions. The nurse had mentioned Melora had been pushed, but the article did not mention this detail. Could it have been covered up? Don�t start looking for ghosts, he thought to himself. He had enough on his mind.\r      If you asked him why he visited the pool the next day, he would not know. He would say, �I just strolled, and there it was waiting.� He walked past the entrance of the natatorium, and the blue water called from the other side of the door�s glass. He had not been looking. And when at first he approached the water, he saw nothing.\r      He could smell bleach and feel the warmth of moisture in the air. His footsteps bounced on the walls at the end of the room. Against the concrete walls, painted grey and white, metal benches waited for swimmers to rest. The only light in the room came from big square windows stacked high on the walls. \r      He stared deep into the water. What are you hiding? he thought. He could have been speaking to the school itself. But this water, this pool, had a deeper secret that it kept to itself. He wondered whether, in twenty years, had the water been changed? Or had the faculty simply bleached it again and again. Could the water that stared up at him be the same water that filled the lungs of Melora Freedman, all those years ago?\r       But it was not water that watched him in that pool house. No, from the depth of the pool, a set of eyes, clear and bright, blinked in the dark. Barty squinted to make out the face. He inched closer, leaning further in. There, right in the middle, in the deepest part, a girl stood staring up at him. Barty understood without thinking. Laurie, the girl he had only met in the Hell Hall, stood under the water. Her stare turned into a grin, satisfied with his glance.\r      Barty did not start. No, Barty froze. His eyes opened wider, as if he could see for the first time in his life. She only mouthed the word �hello.� Instinctively, Barty lifted his hand in greeting, leaning ever closer. He could have fallen in to meet her. She grew closer as he fell forward, losing his balance. In an instant, he would be wet from head to foot.\r      Someone grabbed him by the arm.\r      The effect of the catch had done more than rescue him from a day of wet clothes. It had simultaneously jerked him out of a trance. He looked around at his rescuer, at the face of Mildred. But she did not smile. Instead, concern written like a warning sign on her face, she spoke slowly. �Are you alright?�\r      Barty looked at her in shock, then down at the water. The ghostly image of Laurie had gone now, too soon to point out. \r      �What, what happened,� Barty had to think about every word. His mind had been skipping like a bad internet connection. �Did you, did you see?�\r      �I saw,� Mildred said. �I saw the same thing you saw.�\r      �So, I�m not crazy?� Barty held little comfort with this realization. He had stepped from delusion to despair in a singular moment.\r      �I didn�t say that.� She grinned. �I said I saw her in the hall. I saw her vanish, same as you.�\r      He waited. For what, he did not know. But he wanted to take in the moment. For the first time that he could remember, someone had seen what he saw. And of course it had been her. Everywhere Barty paused to think, he saw Mildred, like a specter in slow motion, everyone else a blur. The question that lingered in his mind, can I trust her? In this moment, he knew. In this sprinkle of time, he could share a drop of kinship with a fellow person. Something happened in that hall, and they both knew it. For the first time in his life, he had a friend.\r      They stood in the bus line, waiting to leave. His eyes, as they usually did, moved from detail to detail. He loathed the students clowning and the noise of the air brakes, squealing as the buses slowed. But today, his eyes drifted to the people walking on the sidewalks outside of the school parking area.\r      The neighborhood around the school had become busier than normal. But amid the joggers and dog walkers, a stranger sat, staring at the boarding students. Something about his oversized clothing, a bit too big for his body, stood out to Barty. Tall and lanky, it seemed as though the correct size did not exist for him. But his appearance did not stir Barty to dread. Rather, the intensity with which he eyed the students, made Barty wonder if the man had been watching him.\r      �Mildred,� he spoke softly. �Do you believe in ghosts?�\r      She turned her head toward him. �Why?�\r      �I�m just struggling to believe, I think.�\r      �Believe in ghosts?�\r      �No,� He shuffled his feet, hands in his pockets. �I�m struggling to believe they don�t exist.�\r      She nodded, noticing his attention elsewhere. She glanced in the direction that he looked and saw the man.\r      �He gives me the creeps,� she said.\r      �Me too,� Barty straightened his voice. �But not, like, a ghost. Just like a person.�\r      She smirked in his direction.\r      �People scare me more than ghosts, Barty.�\r      An obnoxious noise interrupted their musing. Kelly Prescott had just boarded the black sports car that had come for her. She rolled her window down immediately and hung out the side. �Bye, Barty! Don�t forget your suit!� She rode down the driveway, the car horn honking at every car.\r      �Mildred,� Barty said, forgetting his ghostly concerns. �Would you be interested in helping me get out of my date with Kelly?�\r      Mildred watched Kelly drive down the road. Her eyes glistened at the idea. �I would love to help,� she replied.\r      After giving Mildred his number, she promised to call him later that night from her foster parent�s house phone. �They still have one of those?� Barty inquired.\r      She shrugged. �They�re old.�\r      On the phone that night, they brainstormed ideas. �We could cut her hair off�� Mildred suggested the day after in the school hallway. But Barty said that she would just wear a wig. Barty thought about finding a way to make her sick the night of the dance. He did not say this out loud. What if he would want to go with someone else? He would need more advanced notice than the day of the dance.\r      They thought of faking a free vacation the day of the dance. �Too elaborate,� Mildred said. �Plus, she�s rich. She probably goes on vacations all the time. She wouldn�t miss her school dance.� Mildred suggested they get her banned from the dance. �That could work,� Barty thought for a moment about Beau and Preston. �But then again, I�m not sure I want to get anyone else in trouble right now.�\r      They began sitting together at lunch, when she did not disappear, as she often did. In between periods, they walked together and winked in the hall, like co-conspirators, hatching a plan.\r\t�Barty, I do have an idea,� she said one afternoon. �It�s harmless, except for her reputation.�\r      She gave him that sly grin that he had come to enjoy. �I�m listening,� he returned.\r      The following morning, Barty looked for Mildred, but did not see her anywhere. The school had a population of about thirteen hundred, a small number, but not nothing. Even with such a population, Mildred stuck out like a weed among grass.\r      He enjoyed this about her. She largely kept to herself, something they had in common. The way she talked only to necessary people felt akin to himself. But she put electric energy into every conversation, with almost sinister intention. He felt she desired to disrupt the status quo, whatever or wherever that meant.\r      He dismissed these thoughts. I have classes, after all, he thought. Grades still mattered. He needed to focus. The lessons and lectures seemed duller than normal that day, but for his history class. His teacher discussed the Freedmen's Bureau, after the American Civil War, and its opposition. Anything Civil War related always kept his attention.\r      But between classes and at lunch, he ducked and dodged people he knew, especially Kelly. She usually sniffed him out like a hound looking for its favorite place to pee. Somehow, Kelly�s sudden obsession with him made him feel worse than her mocking.\r      Barty loathed the tales of his fight with Beau, even if his peers thought him the hero. But he preferred that kind of attention compared to hearing whispers of �Barty and Kelly.� \r      Barty had unfortunately overheard the school�s couple nickname for him and Kelly. �Barkelly,� a girl mentioned as she retrieved books from her locker. �Barty and Kelly! I never thought they�d get together, but it�s giving goals.� Barkelly? Barty thought. That sounds more like broccoli, his least favorite vegetable. \r      �Barty!� Kelly�s voice woke him from thought. �Barkelly is all the rage right now. How does it feel being popular for once?�\r      �Not good,� Barty replied.\r      She had found him reading in the library. The room had been quiet and dark. Barty found solitude there, except for a brief encounter with Mr. Friend as he left the area. When Kelly peaked through the door window and noticed Barty reading in peace, she chose to disrupt him.\r      Kelly giggled at his response. �You�re so funny, Barty.� Barty glared at her with a deadpan look.\r      �What do you want Kelly?� He cut right to the point. She grinned.\r      �I just wanted to see my Barty Arty.� Barty�s eyebrows rose. �And to remind you that the school thinks we look great together.�\r      �And?� Barty had grown tired of Kelly�s false attempts at casual conversation. He perceived that she spoke every word with selfish ambition.\r      �I need you to know that there is nothing in this world that I want more than to go to the dance with you.� Her grin lowered into a darker, more threatening look. �And nothing in this world will stop that from happening.�\r      Barty closed the book he was reading and plopped it on the desk. �What�s that supposed to mean, Kelly? Speak plainly.�\r      She stepped forward menacingly. Only the desk separated them, and Barty felt like he needed more space. Before he could move, her hands gripped the sides of the desk. She leaned in, her face inching closer to him.\r      �I know you don�t want to go with me, Barty. I�m well aware.� Barty could feel the breath coming off of her words. �But you will go with me. If I have to stuff you and mount you on a stick, you will go with me.�\r      Barty, stunned, leaned his chair back, trying to get away. �Why do you care so much? Why me?�\r      She grabbed his collar, her grip like a gorilla, and pulled their faces together. Her breath smelled of mint.\r      �Because I know about the games you like to play,� she whispered aggressively. �And no matter how dumb you think I am, I assure you. I know enough to beat you.� She smiled, winked, and pecked his nose with a kiss.\r      Barty did not know what to think. Could it be possible that she had caught onto his scheme? The tone in which she spoke felt intentional. She knew something. But how could she know?\r      She stood up straight, and tilted her head, smiling again. �Okay, Pookie?� Then she turned straight around, and marched to the door. �Don�t forget your tux!�\r      When she had finally gone, Barty watched the door, wondering what had just happened. Now the solitude felt more like loneliness, but not because of the lack of people. He craved the company of friends, a feeling most unusual.\r      That evening, Barty performed his nightly ritual with a hopeful feeling. He had longed all that day to speak on the phone with Mildred. He had burned with suspense, thinking about their plan and wondering if she found success.\r      When he dialed her home, he counted the seconds that he waited for her to pick up. He could feel his heart beating in his chest like a drum. His breath seemed to hurt in his lungs. Why did he feel so on edge? He could not explain it.\r      The ringing stopped as a sound clicked on the other side. �Hello?� A stern sounding man had answered the phone. Barty had not prepared for this. Of course he knew someone else could pick up the line, but he had not considered what to say.\r      The words dropped out of his mouth like a stopping faucet, �Is�er� Mildrid there? It�s Barty from school,� he tried to say this warmly, to instill trust. �Barty Beauregard.�\r      �Beauregard?� The man sounded curious. �Like the general?�\r      Barty looked down, exasperated. �No relationship.�\r      The man seemed to ponder for a moment. Then, he spoke. �I�ll see if I can get her. Hold on.�\r      Barty indeed held on, to his shaking legs and his computer desk, which bounced in rhythm. A shuffle occurred on the other end, then words came again. �Hello? Barty?� Mildred spoke these words.\r      Barty immediately felt the tension in his body release. �What took you so long?�\r      �I was in the bathroom,� She replied.\r      �No, I mean at school today,� \r      He could hear her putting something in her mouth and chewing. Mildred liked to eat. She paused chewing and spoke again. �I handled everything. Don�t worry, I�ve done this before.�\r      �I have been thinking�� he began. He detailed the contents of the locker and the school yearbook. He told her about the newspaper article and the nurse�s account. Then, after hearing what he had to say, she responded in a way that perhaps Barty suspected she might.\r      �Barty, we both saw it,� she responded. �You know it, you�re just afraid to say it out loud. But I�m not afraid to say it. Laurie was, or is, Melora Freedman.� \r      Now that the words had been released into the air, they sounded insane.\r      �I� I have a hard time accepting that.� He waited for Mildred to argue with him. But instead she took another bite of food, the crunching coming in loud over the phone.\r      �Why not?� She asked, through the sound of chomping. �Are you afraid of ghosts?�\r      When Barty saw Laurie vanish in the Hell Hall, he did feel afraid. He felt so afraid that he fainted. But why? Why had the apparition left him feeling so broken? Many people feared ghosts. Why should he be any different?\r      �I�m afraid of the implications,� he stated. �Besides, there�s probably a logical explanation.� Or is there, Barty?\r      �Why don�t we just find out?� She replied. �If you�re up for a little investigation.�\r      Barty smiled. �Let�s.�\r      \r\tMonday morning came soon enough. They agreed to venture back together into the Hell Hall, to locker 402. �There�s probably a picture of Melora in the yearbook,� Mildred suggested. If she was a ghost, it should be easy to verify. They simply needed to find an image of the dead girl to verify. Barty agreed.\r\t�There�s no harm in checking.� He reasoned that if the two girls were not the same, then a picture would clear his mind.\r\tHe ate lunch with Mildred, discussing their plans. The cafeteria provided a sense of privacy, because their words could drift into the already present static of conversations. If they discussed something interesting, no one would notice.\r      The menu that day consisted of pizza and salad, and Barty could not stomach pizza. He stabbed his straw into a plastic pouch of milk. �We need to find Gabe.� Gabe was the name of Laurie�s brother.\r      �Would she be upset that you contacted him?� Mildred asked. She had already lifted a large slice of pepperoni to her mouth.\r      �As long as it isn�t too obvious who we are, we�ll be fine,� Barty replied, surveying the room. He always did this, especially when scheming. �How well did you know her?�\r      �Not well,� Mildred replied. �I only ever saw her in the Hell Hall. We ran into each other a few times.�\r      Barty noticed Kelly and her crew walking their trays to a table a few yards away. Barty averted his eyes, hoping she would not notice him.\r      �What?� Mildred asked.\r      Barty motioned with his head. She looked over his shoulder to see the familiar bows of pink moving behind him. \r      Kelly paused behind Barty and looked at the back of his head.\r      �Oh, hello broccoli hair!� Kelly intended this for Barty. Barty�s face flushed, breathing a sigh of exhaustion. �Hello, Kelly.� He turned to greet her.\r      �Oh, so you sit with other girls now?� Kelly used a playful tone. Barty could not tell if she really felt upset. �Lap it up now, goth girl.�\r      Mid-bite, Mildred covered her mouth and turned to the side. She clearly wore a coy smile.\r      �What�s so funny?� Kelly demanded.\r      �It�s just funny,� Mildred replied. �I had no idea you two were that close.�\r      Kelly folded her arms. �It�s not proximity, Smelldrid.� Her goons chuckled at the nickname. �Its possession. My run