        "text": "CHAPTER SIX\rMont Linola Jr. High School, 1999\r      Someone took the yearbook. Barty started a new page in his notebook. This meant he needed a space to write out his thoughts. He scratched his head with his pencil. He had learned not to use ink. Ink meant permanent. Of course, he could have written more. Whatever Laurie had to do with this scheme involved Preston and Beau. It has to be connected, he thought.\r      �Mildred.� Barty decided to ask her the question that had been burning in his mind. The following morning, before classes began, he made his move. �What were you doing, tailing Preston and Beau?�\r      She took a moment to collect her thoughts before speaking. Barty suspected that she might have a lot to say. \r      �At first, I was looking out for Gabe. I met Laurie in the Hell Hall, same as you. But she seemed� weird at first. I thought she must have been hiding there or something. But we started talking about people at school, and people she hated. She mentioned she had a brother that went here. She said that Beau Adams had been following him.�\r      Barty noted that nothing this far seemed different from his own experience. �What did you say to that?�\r      �I said that I knew Beau Adams was a big bully. But she told me that he actually tripped him on the bus and broke his leg.�\r      Barty felt his eyebrows come together in rage. He knew Beau could do something like this. �What did the driver do?� he asked.\r      �Nothing. Or that�s what she said. I offered to keep an eye out for him. That�s when I realized something weird going on. Beau was psycho, like, stalkerish. He would follow Gabe, and ask questions about where he was going. Every spare second, it seemed like he was on him.�\r      �Why?� Barty thought out loud. �That�s some odd behavior. Do you think Kelly knew any of this?�\r      �I don�t think they were that close at all.� She paused to think. �I mean, maybe. Didn�t you say that she threatened you? Like she knew something you didn�t want her to know?�\r      Barty squirmed thinking about this. He remembered too well. �Yes, but I don�t know what that would have to do with Gabe.�\r      �I asked around a little,� Mildred continued. �Some teacher was giving him money. He always had cash on him. But if that was true, it had to be outside of school. And once I found him snooping around in the records room. As far as what him and Preston were up to, I think they must have been in on it somehow. It looked like they were trying to draw me out when they pulled out the knife. But I have no idea how it all fits together.�\r      Barty had to think about this information. He made a few more notes in his notebook.\r      �Mildred, you already know this,� he looked around at a few students whispering across the hall. �I think we need to be careful about who we share with. We need to lay low.�\r      Mildred closed the locker she had been going through, a little too loudly.\r      �Who are you talking to, Barty?� Sarcasm oozed from her words. �Gonna tell Kelly?�\r      Kelly, Barty remembered. How could he have forgotten?\r      Mildred handed him a paper, and his mouth hung open. The school paper had used a picture of Barty and Kelly on the front page. It read �Barkelly? More like �Barfamily�� The boy marveled at Mildred�s ingenuity. �How?� He stared at the page, wondering how the photo had been taken.\r      The news spread like a weed. In History, Barty�s teacher had planned a period of class presentations. A boy named Roy Burkley had a presentation on prominent families in the town of Mont Linola. He had prepared a large poster board with historic pictures of families related to a few prominent students. Where two branches connected, a picture of Barty and a picture of Kelly had been glued in place.\r      One student leaned back in his chair, a look of skepticism on his face. �How did you find this information?�\r      Roy Burkley responded, �I got my information from the Mont Linola Historic Preservation Society.� He even had official emails printed out that confirmed his findings.\r\t�Barty,� said Mr. Hartley, the History teacher. �You and Kelly Prescott could be cousins!� The other students in the class traded whispers, bouncing their eyes from him to their friends.\r      Barty marveled at Mildred�s ingenuity. When Barty made his way to Biology, he noted the students all reading the school paper. They should give her a writing credit, he remarked to himself. Their plan was working.\r\tIn Biology, Mrs. Ravine discussed the dangers of inbreeding. A clownish boy raised his hand and asked, �Mrs. Ravine, if Barty and Kelly turn out to be cousins, what would happen to their kids?�\r      �Well, certainly they couldn�t be too related.� She looked over her glasses at Barty, who shrunk lower in his chair. �I�m sure your children would be beautiful, Mr. Beauregard.� \r      Muffled chuckles from students rumbled in the room. Momentarily, life had left his body. What was I thinking, he pondered. He wanted to get out of his date with Kelly, but did he really think this a good idea?\r      After the third period, Kelly sprang upon him in the hall. �BARTY!� She stomped like a rhinoceros toward her prey. �Have you heard the rumors?�\r      �What rumors?� He scratched his arm, appearing aloof and cool.\r�The rumors that WE�RE COUSINS! You wouldn�t have something to do with this?� He smiled, feeling satisfied. �You think I like the idea that I�m taking my cousin to the school dance?�\r      Her face looked blood red. She stomped her foot on the ground, fists at her side. �If I find out that you�re behind this, I�ll� I�ll�� Barty could have bitten her finger, now pointed to his nose.\r      �You�ll what?� Barty interrupted. �Roy Burkley researched this. Talk to him about it.�\r      With nothing more to say, she marched away, her band of Preppy Pinks following faithfully behind.\r      At lunch, Barty intentionally sought to sit with Kelly.\r      �What are you doing?� She begged, looking like she had seen a ghost. Barty stood over her, holding a tray in his hands.\r      �I just wanted to eat lunch with you, Pookie.� He stole a glance across the cafeteria at Mildred, sitting alone. She returned the look, enjoying the presentation.\r      �You really don�t have to��\r      �I insist,� Barty butt in. �We�re going to be closer when we dance, you know. No need to be afraid of me.� For a moment, she looked frightened. Then, Barty caught a flash of malice in her eyes. He took a seat opposite her, the Preppy Pinks unzipping to let him in.\r      �Oh, but of course,� she returned. �I�ll play along. I�m not afraid of a little attention.�\r      �Of course not,� Barty parried. �You love attention, don�t you?�\r      She looked almost evil. �Not as much as I love power, Barty. And I think I have a little more than you.�\r      Barty took a bit of red beans and rice, the lunch special. It tasted better than normal. Then, after swallowing, he spoke again. �It must run in the family.�\r      \r      During his free period, he spent time in the library. He did not want to return to the Hell Hall quite yet. The corridor had come with a few surprises lately, but he felt he could trust the librarian to keep the stillness of the room. He sat at the same desk that Kelly had earlier put her hands on. He shuddered, thinking back on that afternoon.\r      This day, he had used the computer to find books that might be helpful to his investigation. He searched �Mont Linola,� hoping to find books of local lore and history. He found none. Typical, he thought. Mont Linola had a population of about eleven thousand. Even though its roots stretched back a few hundred years, Mont Linola simply existed.\r      He could not help indulge his more interesting thoughts. He searched for �ghosts� and looked through the lengthy search results. One particular book, Help! My Friend is Dead: Ghosts and How to Talk to Them, seemed interesting. The author went by the name �Adaline Garbotholow,� an unusual combination of letters. Barty clicked the link on the title and glanced through the author information.\r      \rAdaline Garbotholow shares her unique perspective as one who has crossed over and lived to tell the tale. A mystic in the town of Mont Linola, she leads the community in finding peace with their departed loved ones. She has communed with the dead, dined with the departed, and made deals with the devil.\r\r      He scoffed at the description. �How ridiculous,� he said out loud. His voice had carried in the silent library. Barty quickly looked around, hoping to not have disturbed anyone, but he found himself alone.\r      He paused to think. Theoretically, he could meet Adaline Garbotholow if he ever had questions. He remembered the words Susan, the antique shop owner, had told him. Someone in the area did that sort of thing. He wondered whether this was Adaline Garbotholow. He could easily verify the information. If anything, he thought, I could learn something about local spiritual traditions.\r      After attempting to find the book himself, he discovered it was gone from the shelf. He made his way to the librarian�s desk, where a small, greying lady in a floral blouse sat reading her computer screen.\r      �This book is actually checked out right now,� she informed him.\r      �How long will it be out?� \r      She scrolled on her mouse wheel. �It should be returned by Friday. Hopefully the boy returns it on time.�\r      Barty gathered his things to leave. But then, he remembered a book that he could potentially view in the library. The Yearbook. He returned to the librarian�s desk to ask again for help.\r      He cleared his throat to indicate his presence. Noticing him standing there, she looked over her glasses and acknowledged him. �Do you need something else?�\r      �Yes. Do you have old yearbooks here?�\r      �Yes, we do actually,� she replied. Then she raised a boney finger, adorned with a large jeweled ring, and pointed at a line of books atop a short bookshelf. Barty followed her direction hopefully.\r      �They will be in the non-fiction section on top of that shelf. But they aren�t for lending, so you will have to leave them here.� Barty agreed, and thanked her again. Then, he made his way to the corner of the room that she had indicated.\r      Books lined the shirt shelf that divided the seating sections from the back wall of books. He found a set of books that matched. The first spine read, �Mont Linola Junior High School, 1999.� He looked at the following book in line, but noticed it jumped from 1999 to 2001. Distressed, he fingered through the entire collection looking for the missing edition. Double checking, he realized the yearbook did not reside there.\r      He quickly walked through the library, looking at the tables and seating sections. He glanced at the various shelves throughout the room, hoping to see the navy blue binding and gold letters standing out among the shades of colors. But no matter how many looks from the librarian he solicited, he could not find the missing book.\r      Frustrated and defeated, he grabbed the prior yearbook and brought it to his desk. As he thumbed through the pages, he caught the smell of stale paper. In a few places, students had defaced the library copy. When he had gone through all of the class rosters, he frowned. Melora Freedman was not in the yearbook at all. She must not have been at the school this year, he reasoned. Then, he started over and began looking again. He stopped turning when he saw a face he recognized.\r      �Mr. Friend,� he quietly uttered. He had stopped at a class roster page. �Justin Friend.� His face looked softer and his hair thicker. He wore wireframe aviator glasses. The young Friend�s smile seemed as large as the elder Friend's. But, somehow, the photo showed a version that seemed more genuine, unphased by the trials of time.\r      Barty turned through the pages to highlights t