n the face of the woman.\r      �Yes, ma�am,� he replied, glazing quickly at the yearbook. The page had indeed been turned to the photo of his mother, but the red words had vanished. He could feel pain in his head and in his leg where the ghost had bit him. He dared not look during that moment, with the librarian hovering over him. Even if the hag had gone, even if the words had vanished, he still felt the pain. He still knew the truth of the red ink. His mother, indeed, was dead.\r      \r      �It�s still there,� Barty said, a tinge of fright in his voice. He and Mildred had been looking at his leg. There, in the middle of his calf, a circle of cuts had bled all over his skin. �I need to get this treated.�\r      �Will you go to Miss Gerard?� she asked. \r      �No!� he immediately barked. �I don�t want anyone at the school asking questions.�\r      Mildred understood immediately. �Ok, I�ll be right back.� She left him there, in an abandoned restroom. Then after what felt like a lifetime, she returned holding a bottle of alcohol and bandages.\r      �Wow, that�s freaking creepy,� Mildred said with dark fascination. She had patched him up, and they now walked to the bus line. Barty tried hard not to limp, but every step sent pain to his injury. Blood had stained his pants, but he hoped that it could pass for mud. They took their time, allowing students to fly past them.\r      �Dead, dead, dead�� she muttered, looking forward blankly. �Three 'dead�s� Maybe it represents three dead people.�\r      Barty did not want to think about it. But, he knew she could be right. �Who could they be?�\r      �Well, obviously your mother.� Barty frowned. Even though he knew this to be true, somehow the words so casually thrown out seemed to cut.\r      �Obviously,� he repeated.\r      �Sorry, I didn�t mean to��\r      �It�s fine. Continue,� he cut in to stop her sympathizing.\r      �Well your mom, Melora, and maybe�� she hesitated.\r      �What?� Barty prodded. He did not enjoy t