ody cares, Agatha.�\r\t�Remedies for Common Rashes and Infections?� questioned Miss Turnbuckle. �Got an infection, one of you?�\r      Barty and Mildred both turned to each other. Mildred�s mouth hung open in disgust. �Uh, yes. Not me�or Barty�my friend. She�s been bothered by this red, goopy spot on her belly.�\r\tThe Librarian winced. �Oh! Well, shouldn�t she see the doctor? Or even Nurse Gerard?�\r\tMildred hesitated, then spoke. �She�s afraid of medical personnel.�\r\tAgatha gaped at her. �I am not!�\r      The librarian eyed Mildred, squinting slightly. �And Mr. Beauregard knows this friend as well? He seems to be very interested in her fungal health.�\r      �I�m definitely not!� Barty burst. This solicited a smile from the librarian and laughter from the group of friends.\r      �Well, whatever you two need to look for, make sure it�s out in the light. I don�t need any more books disappearing from this library. Do you understand?�\r      The two students traded looks again, then they slowly nodded at her.\r      �I noticed that I couldn�t find a book the other day. The yearbook from 2000. Is that what you�re referring to?�\r      She gave him a stern, confused look, then turned on her heels to the shelf where Barty had found the yearbooks earlier. Barty followed, leaving Mildred�s mysterious friends murmuring and joking about Agatha�s rash.\r      Thumbing through the years, the librarian clucked with her tongue. �Oh! It looks like we have a few missing copies. Indeed, 2000 is missing.� She apologized. �You were looking to see your parents?�\r      Barty looked at her in shock, studying her face.\r      �Barty, I�ve been at this school for thirty years.� She smiled at him. �I knew your parents when they were your age. That�s better than a yearbook, I can tell you that.�\r      Barty felt excitement surge within him. She knew his parents. Who else might she have known? �Did you know Melora Freedman, by chance?�\r      She focused, thinking for a moment. �Is that the girl that went missing?�\r      �No, she didn�t go missing,� Mildred chimed in. She had slowly made her way to where the librarian and Barty stood. �She drowned in the school pool.�\r      �Oh! I remember now.�\r      Barty�s head spun with questions. �You mean a girl went missing?�\r      She frowned momentarily. �Mont Linola is an old school, Barty. Almost eighty years old. Things are bound to happen. Why, I remember a poor couple that died in a car accident, just before their school dance. It�s life, dear boy.�\r      �Or death, you mean,� Mildred corrected her.\r      �Touch�!� She smiled at Mildred�s play on words. Apparently even the librarian enjoyed a bit of dark humor. �But I do seem to remember that shortly before that awful accident in the pool, there was a girl that had gone missing. Everyone was so upset about it. Just up and ran away, or something like that.�\r      �You don�t remember her name?� Barty pressed.\r      The librarian started back to her desk. �I�m afraid I don�t, Mr. Beauregard.�\r      He frowned. Of course other kids went missing, he thought. For a moment, he pondered asking Mildred�s friends. He looked back at them. Kenny had been throwing his arms out wildly, doing an imitation of someone. The others were laughing, as if they cared little about the library's code of quiet. I wonder where they went? He thought to himself. He wondered how many students had died over the years. \r      Barty and Mildred, now loaded down with yet another question, left the library and headed toward the bus exit.\r      �Barty, what's up?� Mildred asked, noticing Barty had worn a serious face for all of five minutes.\r      �I think we should steal the yearbook,� he said quietly. �The �99 yearbook, I mean.�\r      She stopped, making him wait, and swung her bag around. After checking the hall, she opened the zipper.\r      �You didn�t!� Barty said, fully aware of the answer.\r      �I did.� She reached in and pulled up the corner of a large, navy blue book. Gold letters began to shimmer from the spine. Barty recognized it immediately. He surveyed her face momentarily. Then, he smiled. �Good move.�",
