        "text": "CHAPTER EIGHT\r      On Monday, Mr. Friend greeted Barty in his usual, friendly way. But Barty sensed something in his demeanor had changed. He seemed nervous and fidgety. �Are you alright, Mr. Friend?�\r      �Yes, I�m fine, Barty!�\r      Barty did not believe him in the slightest. His hair seemed brushed, but slightly greasy as if he had not showered. Barty also noticed that his glasses had smudges on them, whereas normally, he polished them frequently. His fingernails had been peeled off, and his hands were dry and scaly. His shirt had more wrinkles than a used ball of aluminum foil. He hasn�t been taking care of himself, Barty suspected.\r      �You knew my dad, right?�\r      Mr. Friend shifted in his seat, almost spitting out his coffee.\r      �What�er, yes, yes I did,� the man responded, apparently surprised by the question. �How did you know?�\r      Barty sat straight up in his chair. He looked down to the right, thinking for a moment. Should I say? He debated if he should reveal where he had seen the picture of Mr. Friend and his father. If Mr. Friend had indeed stolen the yearbook, would he also go back for the 1999 edition?\r      �I heard from my dad that he knew you.� He lied.\r      Mr. Friend, or Justin, had a look of suspicion growing behind his glasses. �When was this?�\r      �A few months ago.� Barty lied again. He did not mention the yearbook or the happenings at school. \r      �That�s interesting, I think.� The man straightened himself in his seat. \r      �How so, Mr. Friend?� Barty�s eyebrows gave away his suspicion. �Is it odd that he would mention you? Did you two get along?�\r      �Oh yes! We got along swimmingly.� He smiled, reaching for trinkets on the desk. He seemed to fidget over this information, which made Barty want to pry further. �Did you know Melora Freedman?�\r      The man eyed him, stunned. �No. Who is that?�\r      Barty glared at him. Probably, if he could see in a mirror, he would have scared himself. Instinctively, he knew the counselor had lied.\r      �Barty,� the man continued. �We spoke about your mom in the past, and how you wish you could remember more about her. Have you spoken to your dad about this?�\r      Barty paused to think before responding. This is a game, I�m sure of it. Justin must have something to hide, but what? And why? Did his relationship to Barty�s dad have something to do with Melora Freedman�s death? Play along, Barty, he reminded himself.\r      �Yes,� Barty finally responded. �I think I�m beginning to remember some things.�\r      This prompted energy in the school counselor. He reacted, leaning forward slightly. �Like what, Barty?� Barty studied his movements, hoping to read something in his body language.\r      �Her smile. Her curly hair. The sound of her voice.�\r      �The sound of her voice? That�s amazing. How do you feel when you think about her?�\r      Barty sunk. His eyes drifted downward, staring into the universe. �I� uh� I feel lost.� He did not lie now. He could feel emotion rising to the surface.\r      A phone buzzed on the table. Barty�s eyes searched for the source of the noise. Mr. Friend quickly picked up the phone and flipped it open. �I�m so sorry, Barty. I have to take this. It�s very important.� He lifted the phone to his ear, and walked out the room. Barty tried to listen to what he had to say. When he closed the door, Barty heard the conversation as low rumbles. \r      He found it odd and inappropriate that Mr. Friend would take a call during their appointment. Unless, of course, the issue had to do with student safety. He could not hear the words clearly. The counselor�s voice carried in muffled sounds, indiscernible.\r      Barty looked around the room. Perhaps, if Mr. Friend had something going on, he could find something. But should he? What would Mildred do? He searched the desk with his eyes. The desk faced the wall, a laptop open to the left side so that only Mr. Friend could read the screen. The counselor used it to take notes occasionally. Barty shifted to his left in order to spy the screen. As he leaned, the screen came into view, quickly showing a locked sign-in screen. No luck.\r      His eyes moved from left to right, taking in the desk toys and coffee cup rings. Mr. Friend had bought a custom mousepad. It had been printed with a picture of Mr. Friend and his husband posing at a themepark. They looked incredibly happy. In their own awkward way, they matched each other's style, like a complementary set of salt and pepper shakers.\r      Above the desk, Mr. Friend hung a school calendar. The school dance had been circled on the fourth week. He had also scribbled notes and circled dates when he would be out. Nothing immediately seemed out of the ordinary, but Barty took a picture of the calendar with his phone to survey later. \r      The door handle wiggled, and Barty�s heart leapt. He thrust his phone under his thigh, just in case Mr. Friend had seen something. Barty could hear the voice clearer now, saying, �No, I know, Carrie. But we can discuss this outside of business hours. Okay? Oh. Really? Well, I�m going to let�� The voice trailed off as footsteps became more distant.\r      Barty peered under the desk. The garbage can seemed to glow from within it. Barty suspected this to be a fallen item, like a flashlight or a phone. His curiosity prodding him on, he knelt down to survey the contents of the can, almost hidden in shadow.\r      Barty reached into the garbage can carefully. He disliked garbage altogether. But this seemed worth the grime. The light seemed to be coming from some paper on the inside. Odd as this struck him, when he pulled the paper out into the light of the lamps in the room, the glowing ceased. He blinked. Had he imagined it?\r      The thick paper turned out to be a postcard. On the photoside, it had, printed on it, a photo of a Confederate Statue, a familiar sight in the City across the lake. On the letter side, someone had scrawled a note in nearly illegible hand. Barty could make out the signature just enough to read, �Remember, Steamy.�\r      His eyes glanced to the cloth of his pants, now illuminated with a soft white glow on the underside of the card. He flipped the card over again, but nothing happened. The glowing ceased. It must be too bright, he reasoned. And indeed, one could argue that the room, lit by lamps rather than overhead fixtures, could not be described as bright.\r      He raised his feet to the chair, bringing his knees close to his face. He cupped his hands around the photoside, providing a sample of darkness to the paper. Under his hands, some faint lettering appeared.\r      At that moment, the door ripped open, as Mr. Friend, flustered and elevated by the phone call, returned into the room. �I�m so sorry, Barty!�\r      Barty flattened his hands against the paper, hiding it. Simultaneously, his feet returned to the floor. Mr. Friend noticed this and frowned a small disappointed look. �Barty, maybe try not to put your feet on the chair. Leather, and all.�\r\tBarty apologized, then made an excuse. �Mr. Friend, it�s getting late.�\r\tThe counselor glanced at the time on his computer. Barty used this opportunity to shove the card into his pocket. Then, Mr. Friend, surprised at the time, replied, �Oh, sweet heavens. You�re right! Better head off to class.� He walked to the door and held it open for Barty.\r      �Once, again. I�m so sorry for the distraction.�\r\tBarty nodded silently, and exited, thinking more about the postcard than Mr. Friend�s lack of professionalism. He raced against the school bell, straight to a janitor�s closet. He jiggled the door handle and found it open. Once inside, he closed the door, suddenly wrapped in darkness. He pulled the postcard out, and indeed, letters shone brightly in the shadows of the room. Large letters had been etched into the glossy coating of the photo on the card. It seemed as though light pierced through the scratches in the paper, like a crack in a wall.\r     BARTY BEAUREGARD,\r     BE CAREFUL WHO YOU TRUST. I�ll see you soon.\r- A REAL FRIEND\r\r\tThen, as if pulling him back to reality, the bell rang.\r      He stared down at the postcard, fascinated by the glowing light behind the lettering. A real friend? What could this mean? Barty felt certain that it could be a nod toward Mr. Friend himself. Perhaps the author of the note wanted to warn the boy of Justin Friend�s true motives. But on another, darker note, could it be a warning that Mildred could not be trusted?\r\tHe turned and reached for the handle of the closet in which he had hidden, still studying the postcard as he turned the latch. His wrist stopped turning as the handle hit an invisible wall. The door was locked from the outside. This can�t be, Bart thought momentarily, remembering the locked door in the library. He remembered the horrifying face of the woman. He tried again and again, shaking the handle with increasing desperation.\r\tHe banged his closed fists against the door, the postcard bouncing back and forth with each swing. �Hello!� he called. �Can someone help, please?� He continued swinging his hands against the golden, lacquered wood of the door. Why would someone design a door to lock like this? But no matter how hard he beat, no one came. He yelled, calling with as much volume as he could muster. �Someone, HELP!�\r\tNothing. No one came. He turned back around and leaned against the doorway, breathing hard. He was trapped.\r\tA few moments passed. He surveyed the card again, reading the letter, but it had been too dark. He turned the light on, hoping to make out the scrawled handwriting. He squinted and made out the first few lines. After a few tries, rereading and rewriting in his mind, he felt confident that he could understand the message.\r\t\rI�m coming soon. We need to talk in person. I have not found Bullet. Beware the boy.\r- Remember, Steamy\r      Barty bit his lip, carefully reading the words again and again. There must have been a clue hidden in the words. Bullet? Steamy? These must have been code words or nicknames. Unless, of course, someone had been shot. But who was the boy?\r      Barty fell backwards, the door he leaned on suddenly giving way. Now on the floor, he leaned against the legs of someone he did not yet know.\r      �What are you doing, hiding in the closet?� Barty sprang to his feet, hiding the postcard, and turned around. Before him stood Coach Grant, wearing the tiniest khaki shorts and yellow collared shirt. \r      �I got locked in. Someone pushed me in and closed the door.� Perhaps this lie would provoke empathy from the thin man. Certainly, he understood bullies.\r      The tall, awkward man bent over. Looking over his dark, aviator glasses, he eyed Barty. �What�s that in your pocket?�\r      �Why do you care? It�s none of your business.�\r      The coach leaned closer in, yet another person putting his face grossly close to Barty�s. The boy could almost see his reflection in the glass of his spectacles. �Give it to me.� His breath hit Barty in the face. It smelled like peppermint.\r      Barty felt as though he had no choice. He reached in and gave the man what he required. The coach looked at it, front and back, and opened the pages. �Your diary?� He chuckled to himself. �You should have just said so. But you had to act like a criminal.�\r      He handed the book back to Barty, who tucked it into his pants pocket. He relaxed, realizing the coach did not enjoy reading enough to actually look through the contents.\r      �I have to get to class, Coach Grant. May I go?�\r      The coach chewed gum and paused, clearly icing Barty.\r      �Principle Green wants you in his office,� he paused again. �I hope you aren�t in trouble.� He said this through a toothy grin.\r      The coach led Barty down the halls of the school toward the front lobby. The administrative wing branched off the main entrance, behind the front desk. Barty walked through the desk to the familiar waiting room, just outside of Principal Green�s office. He had been here several times before. Most recently, he waited here with Mildred after the bleacher incident.\r      Coach Grant knocked on the door, which swiftly opened. �Wait here for a minute,� he instructed Barty. The door closed, leaving Barty to his thoughts. Then after a moment, Coach Grant exited the room again, and nodded at the already anxious boy. �Have a good day, Mr. Beauregard.� Then, Barty entered the room slowly, surveying the situation.\r      �Barty! How wonderful it is to see you again!� A tall man in a grey suit stood to greet him.\r      �Mr. Webster,� Barty responded. Frank Webster held his hand out, but the boy did not accept it. By reputation, the man only came around bearing bad news.\r      �By wonderful, we mean unfortunate,� said his twin, wearing the same suit and red glasses.\r      �Mr. Webster,� Barty spoke to Loyd, always honest and tactless.\r      Mr. Green felt the need to greet Barty as well, so he chimed in from behind his desk. �Barty! I hope you�re ehaving a fabulous day. Take a seat, son.� Barty complied, his eyes moving between the three men.\r      �Why am I here?�\r      �Barty, we don�t know how to tell you this,� Frank began. He held his hands together, looking down.\r      �I�m really sorry, Barty,� Mr. Green said mournfully. �We just have some awful news. It was reported recently��\r      �Your dad is dead,� Loyd finished. �Most likely shot in his car. Not good, not good.�\r      Nothing could have prepared him for this outcome, although death seemed most likely. Mr. Beauregard was nothing if not a good man. Sure, Barty could have assumed, like others, that he had simply run from legal troubles. Kelly once suggested that Barty�s father had a gambling problem and needed to hide. But Barty knew better than all the rest. No, his father would come home no matter what. Barty hated the truth, but it stood that only a tragedy would keep his father away. Even knowing this, Barty�s heart stopped.\r      �It broke an hour ago, Barty.� Mr. Green, anxious to be of use, leaned into his computer monitor and read aloud. ��Beauregard�s car has been found in Lafreaux, submerged in a tributary of Lake Philippas. No body has been found as of an hour ago. Authorities say the side of the vehicle had been riddled with what appeared to be bullet holes.� I�m afraid, Barty, that the writing is on the walls.�\r      Loyd Webster turned to face Barty directly. �Your father is dead. It is very probable that he was murdered.�\r      The words hit Barty in the face. Murdered. Could this truly be?\r      �But they didn�t find his body?� Barty argued. �How can you say he�s dead without his body?�\r      Frank, sympathetically, began to explain. �Barty, it�s obvious to us. Legally, it�s not enough to declare him dead. But our company cannot continue paying for your care, considering the circumstances.�\r      �The police are searching the rivers and surrounding woods,� Loyd explained. �Even if they don�t find him, there�s enough evidence to suggest that he won�t be returning to us.�\r      Barty�s mind reeled with questions. Would Sarah be able to take care of him anymore? What would happen to him now?\r      Frank spoke again. �I spoke to Judge Carson. He�s in charge of your case��\r      Barty stood up at these words. �My case? What do you mean?�\r      All three of the adults in the room traded looks, as if wondering who should speak.\r      Frank leaned forward to where Barty stood. �Barty, unless your dad is found, you will become a ward of the state.�\r      A ward of the state, Barty heard the words and repeated them in his mind. How could this have happened? �Doesn�t he have a will? Didn�t he make plans for this?� Barty sounded desperate, because he felt that way. \r      �There is a will,� Frank continued. �But it doesn�t go into effect unless he�s dead.�\r      �So where will I go?� Barty questioned.\r      Loyd spoke again. �If your dad doesn�t turn up within seven days, you will go into the Child Welfare Department�s care. From there, we cannot guarantee what will happen. But Sarah does not have permanent legal guardianship over you.� Barty appreciated the blunt way that he spoke, even if it came across the wrong way. No B.S.\r      The two attorneys left the office after saying their goodbyes. Barty did not know what to think. Seven days. No body.\r      �Barty,� Mr. Green began. �I�ve been told that you�ve been snooping around the school, asking questions, and things of the sort. Hiding in closets and such.�\r      Barty looked up at him. Why are you asking me about this? He thought.\r      The principal continued. �I would like to encourage you not to look for trouble. Mont Linola Junior High is a good, safe school. We don�t have ghosts lurking around every corner, young man.� He peered down on Barty, as if trying to read his face.\r      Barty felt indignant. He had just been informed that his father had likely been murdered, but Mr. Green seemed concerned about the school�s reputation.\r      �Principal Green,� he replied. �Ghosts are just people hiding in the dark.�\r      The principal's eyes grew wide. �Well,� he said softly. �I�m sure if anyone is hiding anything, I will be sure to find out.�\r      Barty understood. �I�m sure you will.� They stared at each other, waiting for the other to move. Then, Mr. Green flinched, making room for Barty to leave.\r      Walking through the hallway felt like a walk in the spotlight. The walls and lockers appeared darker than normal. Students stopped and watched as Barty made his way to his locker to collect his things. News traveled fast, but how could everyone at school already know?\r      Though a class waited for him, he did not walk there. Instead, he wandered aimlessly, as if guided by a force he did not know. Turning a corner, he moved into the main corridor of the school, lined with posters and displays, highlighting the school�s achievements. In one lit case, he saw trophies from the football team�s most recent year. Gold metal glistened against the lights, filling the case with a warm glow. A wall next to the shelf displayed pictures from each year�s previous team. The chess team even had a panel.\r      Looking for a glimmer of hope, he perused the different sections until he found the bulletin board that featured the swim team. Mont Linola Junior High did not have a swim team until 1998, when the school built the indoor pool. Pictures of each team filled the board in a grid, the year and awards listed on engraved plaques under the framed photos.\r      1998, 1999, Barty read to himself. He did not expect to see the year 2000. And indeed, he did not. The photo had been skipped over. Who�s hiding at Mont Linola? He thought to himself. \r      Almost automatically, his eyes wandered to the photo of the year before. One girl stuck out like a sore thumb; his mother. He knew her instantly, her mixed girl curls and brown skin, darkened by exposure to the sun. He had seen her face in the 1999 yearbook as well as his own family photos, taken in a mall somewhere long before he could remember.\r      If something did not turn up soon, he would have to live someone. Who would he go to? His father had not spoken about her side of the family much. Most of his family seemed like strangers. Barty�s grandparents had died already, and he had been an only child.\r      I am� an orphan. He thought, a tear forming on his cheek. \r      �Barty Beauregard.� A voice interrupted his moment of silence.\r      Barty turned to see a boy, about his own height, standing in the distance. He had neatly brushed, black hair that looked wet. His eyes drooped, dark circles resting beneath them as if he had an iron deficiency. He looked tired.\r      �Gabe De Vera?� Barty returned, quickly wiping the tear from his cheek with his shoulder.\r      Barty had not noticed Mildred, standing behind him. He had fixated on the boy, the answer to his questions. But now, he realized that she must have retrieved him. She looked at him, almost communicating silently with her eyes.\r      �Yes, that�s me.� He looked over his shoulder meekly. �She said you needed to see me.�\r      Barty thought for a moment. How would he ask what he needed to know? How did one go about asking about another�s possible dead sister?\r      �Gabe, do you have any siblings?� He thought this seemed innocuous enough.\r      Gabe�s eyes darted left and right, thinking about the questions as if trying to read Barty�s mind. �I�I do.� He stuttered. �I have a sister, Fionna, and a brother, Donni.�\r      He moved closer to Gabe, like a lion closing in on his prey. �Gabe, I should have been more specific.� he paused for a moment. �Dead siblings?�\r      The boy looked frightened for a moment, as if Barty had looked deep into his soul. And indeed, Barty�s eyes seemed brighter, as if they had an internal light.\r      �I have a sister that died, but I never met her.� At this, Barty could feel the wheels turning in his mind. Finally, he could find an answer to the question of Laurie�s appearance. Laurie, who had not been seen since the day she glowed bright in the Hell Hall, seemed to plague him every moment.\r      �Her name was Melora,� Barty spoke low.\r      Nothing came for a split second, making him question his frankness. Then, the words came from Gabe in a slow, soft answer. �Yes. How did you know that?�",
