        "text": "CHAPTER NINE\rThe Three Visitors\r      Barty had little time to process the events at Mont Linola Junior High. His life, already broken in a million pieces, had again been stirred by the invisible spoon of fate. And yet, sometimes he wondered whether the spoon had been attached to some other force, some person or deity bound on making a mess of his school years.\r      Upon arriving at home, he immediately changed and broke out his notebook. He began scribbling out all of the thoughts and events that had occurred during the previous few weeks. A ghost had met him in the Hell Hall. At least, he felt sure that it had been a ghost. Could she have been someone pretending to be the ghost of Melora Freedman? This could have been true, but at least now he could tie the two identities together.\r\tHe lifted his leg and examined the place where the old hag had bitten him. Where once a circle of cuts had stained his pants, only fresh skin existed. Miraculously, the scars had disappeared. Interesting, he thought. But at this point, he knew better than to write the incident off as a hallucination.\r\tDead, dead, dead� the woman had said.\r\tCoinciding with this thought, three knocks came from the living room door. Then, feet shuffled to answer. Barty could hear Sarah�s voice from down the hall. �Oh, hi! Come in. Do you want coffee?�\r\tBarty did not have to wonder who this could be. He already knew. Someone had found his dad�s car in a river. Now, the investigation would begin.\r      �Does your dad have any enemies?� the detective asked, his moustache bouncing up and down with every word.\r      They sat at the dining room table in Barty�s home as the boy thought about the question. He could not think of a single person that would hate his father. In fact, he could recall on one hand the number of times his father had spoken ill of someone.\r      There had been times when he dueled with teachers. Barty, when younger, brought trouble upon himself for arguing with them in class. �He was right, though,� he would say.\r      �But he corrected me in front of the class, Mr. Beauregard,� his fourth grade teacher replied.\r      �And?� Barty�s dad had a way of speaking. �Do you want to be embarrassed or ignorant? I don't understand.�\r      Barry understood his teachers did not appreciate this type of direct confrontation. Would one of them have killed him over it? Certainly not.\r      �Not that I can think of,� Barty replied to the officer.\r      Detective Sheff did not wear a trenchcoat, like Sherlock Holmes. Instead, he wore a white fishing shirt and blue jeans. On his feet, the leftovers of an alligator slept, shaped into brown pointed boots. His face seemed to be stuck in a skeptical scowl.\r      �What about girlfriends?� The detective continued prodding. �Did he ever go on dates or meet anyone?�\r      Barry thought about it. He could not recall the last time his dad had taken someone out. Once, Sarah had come to sit with him while his dad went on a date. When the man returned, he immediately changed clothes and slumped in his chair. �That was a big mistake, Barty.� He looked rough, beaten up.\r      This had been years ago, and Barty certainly could not remember anything about the woman.\r      �Not for a long time,� he stated, wondering if his dad missed being in love.\r      Detective Sheff looked at another police officer standing in the room. Then, he pulled out a photo and laid it on the table. There, a screen capture from a security camera showed Andrew Beauregard, seated at a table across from a woman. She wore a scarf around her head and colorful, flowing fabric for clothes. Her earrings, large gold medallions, reflected the bright sunlight.\r      �This was taken at Cafe Lagrange,� the detective stated. �Do you recognize her?�\r      Barty stared at the photo, trying to read his father�s body language. In a way, his smile seemed relaxed, but his seated position appeared hunched forward, focused. If anything, Barty could tell that his dad did not look at ease. He appeared nervous. He wore his typical attire�a collared plaid button up and navy blue chico pants. If the camera had captured a moment from a date, Andrew Beauregard had not gone out of his way to look more impressive than he did every day.\r      �I don�t know her,� Barty replied. �Who is she?�\r      Detective Scheff�s face twisted into a smile for perhaps the first time since entering the house. �Adoline Garbotholow. She�s batshit crazy, I can tell you that.�\r      Barty sat up when he heard the name. �The spiritualist?�\r      �She�s a fortune teller or something. As far as I�m concerned, she�s a total fraud. I don�t believe in the stuff myself,� the detective replied. �You sure you don�t know her?�\r      Barty thought back to the library. He recalled reading about her from the biography on the school computer�that day. It was the day that the woman chased him in the library. He could still remember the claw-like nails that nearly cut his neck. He could feel her cold, lifeless fingers wringing his neck.\r      �Barty?� Sheff said, trying to make the boy snap back to attention. This worked. Barty jerked back to life, suddenly wide awake.\r      �The lady that owns the antique shop by the lakefront told me about her.�\r      The detective picked up the photo and returned it into a manilla folder. Then, he pulled a card out of his pocket and placed it in front of Barty. �Call me if you think of something.� He stood up to leave, then paused, staring at the boy. �Call me if you need anything. Anything at all. I�m going to figure this out. When I do, we will bring whoever did this to justice.�\r      When he had finally gone, Barty got up to leave the table.\r      �Barty, do you want dinner?� Sarah called out after him as he walked down the hall.\r      �No,� he replied. He had other things on his mind.\r      He returned to the notebook, spread out on his desk. Adoline Garbotholow, he thought, writing the words on the page. The fact that his father had met her did not necessarily mean anything. But why would his dad have neglected to mention it?\r      Then, Barty heard three more knocks on the door. Again, feet shuffled to answer.\r      �Oh, hello, Miss Higgins,� Sarah said, opening the door. �Yes, come on in. Do you want some coffee?�\r      This time, Barty could not be sure who Miss Higgins could be. He made his way down the hall as the tall, slender woman entered the home. She looked around, almost intentionally investigating, when she met eyes with him. �Oh, are you Barty?�\r      He had never met a woman so tall and commanding. She wore a black leather jacket, blue jeans, and a giant gun at her side. Her voice sounded like something out of an old western. Indeed, she looked the part. Around her neck, a badge hung that read �Darcy Higgins, DCFS.� \r      �I am,� Barty replied, still taking in the sight of her.\r      They again sat at the table, while the woman looked over a pile of papers. She asked dozens of questions about Barty and Sarah�s life. It seemed as if she wanted to know everything about him, even his dietary preferences.\r      �Mont Linola Junior High,� Sarah responded. �Thirteen� June twenty-first, 2010.�\r      �And you, Barty,� she said, turning to him. �You feel safe with Sarah?�\r      He looked at his caretaker. Her mouth hung open for the first time that afternoon. Then, he replied to Darcy Higgins, �I feel as safe as any boy could feel, considering the facts.�\r      �What are the facts, Barty?� She returned, cooly.\r      �Someone killed my dad, right?�\r      The woman smiled at him. Not a smile of satisfaction or joy. This smile meant, �I know you don�t believe that. You�re smarter than you look.�\r      �Right.� She looked at Sarah and sighed. �You don�t have guardianship over him beyond your employment with his company. That�s going to end soon, so Barty is going to have to go to someone that we can verify is related to him. Either that, or he�ll have to go into one of our foster homes.�\r      Sarah nearly leapt out of her chair. Standing, she walked behind Barty, ready to grab him and run. �No! There�s no way I�ll let that happen.�\r      Darcy stood up, ready to leave. �It�s not up to you, Miss Badeaux. It�s the way it has to be. Now look, he has family on his mother�s side. They don�t too far away. Maybe you can keep in contact once we�ve placed him in a stable home.� She walked to the door and opened it. �I�ll be in touch.�\r      Barty remembered the Family Reunion invitation that Mrs. Prescott had given him. He wondered what a family reunion might look like on his mothers side. �Your mom was Creole,� his dad had told him. Barty understood this as a great blend of cultures, some Native and some European. It meant a gumbo of French, English, Spanish, African, and Native American. Mixed, he thought.\r      Mr. Beauregard had lined the house with family pictures of Barty�s mom, Tula. However, the professional family portraits stopped when she died. In their stead, pictures of vacations, go kart outings, and fancy dinners had taken their place. Mr. Beauregard could not replace Tula, but he did his best to make sure Barty had a good childhood.\r      Barty always marveled at how beautiful his mother appeared. She had soft, light brown skin and curly dark hair that fell when long enough. She looked lean and tall, with high cheekbones. And she smiled in every picture. Barty felt sure that if she had been alive, he would certainly enjoy being with her.\r      But why had he not met any of her family? Why had Andrew Beauregard kept this part of his family away? He had rarely thought about this at home. He just thought it was normal. But now, a thirteen year old experiencing disillusionment, he realized this could not be normal. Unless, of course, something had happened. Perhaps, his father had a falling out with her family. But what could have happened?\r      Sarah laid her head down on the table, and beat it with her fist. �Barty, this is the worst.� When she raised her head again, tears had filled her eyes.\r      �I know,� Barty replied. �No one wants to drink your coffee.�\r      He started walking back to his room, slowly. The light bulb in the middle of the hall had begun to flicker. Then, with a popping sound, it went dark. Barty walked to the lightswitch and started flipping it up and down, but the fixture did not respond. He breathed out loudly, knowing that the bulb would need to be replaced.\r      On the right side of the hallway, from under a door, a blue light stretched across the wood of the floorboards. Several times a day, Barty passed this doorway on the way to his room. It led to his father�s home office, a room that Barty dared not enter without permission. �You�re not allowed in here without me,� his father had said. �I�ve got a lot of records from a lot of clients here, and it�s all very confidential.� Now, Barty wondered whether the rules applied if his dad could not enforce them.\r      For the first time since seeing his father at home, Barty put his hand on the brass knob. It felt cold, unused. As he applied pressure to turn the metallic ball, it stuck a little. Are you sure? It asked. I am, Barty replied. He applied slightly more pressure and felt the mechanism give way with a clicking feeling. Then, the door opened freely. \r      Barty pushed the door into the office and stepped inside. The room felt cold and untouched. His dad�s desk had papers sprawled all over the top of it. Bookshelves lined one wall, and a single window allowed moonlight to enter the room. \r      Barty walked around to the other side of the desk and sat in the large, black computer chair. He could smell the faint traces of his father�s cologne on the leather of the chair, taking him back to when his dad could still hold him. He momentarily paused, leaning back into the chair and closing his eyes.\r      Then, after a moment, he opened them. He saw everything in the room. Supernatural light seemed to guide him. One particular book glowed in the darkness. Barty had not seen it there, and indeed he had not previously needed to.\r      He walked around the desk again to the shelves of books lining the wall opposite the desk. Then, he squatted down and squinted in concentration. There, on the bottom shelf, his dad kept old magazines, photo albums, and memorabilia. Along with hobby books and collector sets, he kept a copy of a navy blue book. On its spine, Barty could see the gold letters that read Mont Linola Junior High School, 1999.\r      As he began to reach out and grab the book, someone knocked on the door three times. He looked at the source and whispered, �Yes, Sarah?�\r      No answer returned.\r      Barry stood and walked to open the door. When he pulled it open, he found no one on the other side. His hands shook as he ushered the door to its place. Maybe I imagined it, he thought. \r      �What are you doing in this room?� A familiar voice asked.\r      Barry would have jumped had his blood not run cold. Slowly, his body swiveled to look at the person. Slumped in the black chair, a man sat, wearing a tattered plaid shirt. His straight black hair ran into his face in wet bunches that led to strings of water. The man looked like he had just stood up in a pool, dripping at every sharp point on his body.\r      �I told you never to come in here without me,� he continued.\r      Barty�s words became lodged in his throat. He knew this man. He knew his eyes, his hands, and the gold digital watch that clung to his wrist. He knew immediately by the sound of his voice and the way he slumped in the chair, tired and ready to rest.\r      The familiarity did not scare him. No, it was the unfamiliar that cut deep. He did not recognize the bags under the man�s eyes or the way his chest heaved up and down with labored breaths. He had never seen the bloodshot, half open eyes of a the man, strangled with pain.\r      �Are you going to,� the man coughed, and, as he did, water came out of every hole on his face. �Say something?�\r      �I�m,� Barty choked. �I�m sorry, dad.�\r      The man glared at him, not in an angry way. He looked disappointed, but in what Barty did not know. Had his face not already been wet from whatever water had taken him, tears would have been there.\r      �It�s not your fault,� the man returned, attempting to sit up. He slipped as he pushed up on the arms of the chair. As he did, his hands seemed to pass through the plastic arm rests, offering no support.\r      Barty inched closer, hoping to make the man see him again. Closer now, he could see the clothing covered in dirt and tears and blood. Bits of grass and pine needles lay like remnants of a roll on the ground.\r      Finally, Andrew stood. His legs passed through the chair like water, and he walked around the desk to where Barty stood. His feet made squishing noises, leaving wet footprints in the carpet.\r      �You hate being wet,� he said, almost smiling.\r      Barry could not hold the tears back any longer. He started to cry, as he did, he threw himself forward into the man�s torso. His father wrapped his arms around him and squeezed. They stayed that way, softly crying in each others arms, knowing the truth. Barty instinctively understood that this would be his last chance to feel the warmth of his father�s embrace. However, after the minutes passed, only cold, like a wet winter coat, came from the man�s body. \r      �I�m so sorry, son. I�m so sorry,� the man cried, resting his head on Barty�s curly tufts of hair. �I should have come home. I should have��\r      �You should have what?� Barty questioned, almost angrily. He let go and backed away slowly to face the man. �What happened? Who did this to you?�\r      Andrew Beauregard did not respond. He looked straight into the boy�s face for a moment before drifting off into silent memory. He looked through Barty,  studying the nothingness of the moment.\r      �Dad?� Barty spoke again.\r      �I don�t know.�\r      �You don�t know?� Barty repeated. This had not been the answer he hoped for. In this moment, he felt as if all of his questions could be settled, but his father�s response indicated differently.\r      �Dad, I need to know everything you remember. I need to know. I have to find out who�� his voice drifted off, not wanting to finish the sentence.\r      �Who killed me?� Andrew finished. �Barty, there�s a lot you don�t know. God, there's a lot I don�t know. I was driving, and I heard gunshots. And everything went black.�\r      �Where were you?� Batty prodded.\r      �I was� I was�� he stumbled, grabbing his midsection. Then, he lurched forward and vomited. A fast stream of water sprayed from his mouth and filled the floor. �I�m dead, Barty! I'm dead, I'm dead, I'm dead�� He started wailing and hyperventilating. �I�m dead! I died, Barty! I'm sorry! I'm so sorry!�\r      Barry walked forward, reaching for his icy hand. He too cried, but softly, trying to remain in control. �It�s okay, dad. I'm fine. I'll be okay.� Barty knew this to be a lie. He did not feel capable of working out the issues before him. He felt alone.\r      �You will,� the man replied. �You�re strong.�\r      Barry did not say anything in response. Instead, he thought carefully about the words he should utter next. He longed to savor this moment, however horrible, and simply exist with his father. He wanted to reminisce and laugh and suggest watching an episode of Go Fireboy, Go. But the questions loomed too loudly. He needed answers. His father dying, or, rather dead, had little time. Instinctively, Barty knew he would only have this moment before his dad would vanish into the eternity beyond.\r      �Dad, I am going to find out what happened. I promise you. And I'm going to make it right,� Barty said. He looked at his father in the face, catching his attention. �You have to tell me everything you know about what I ask. Okay?�\r      His father nodded. �I�ll try. No, wait,� he snapped back to attention, coughing and wheezing. �You can�t, son. Don't get involved with this. Leave it to the police.�\r      Barty met his eyes with frightening determination. �I will do what I want. You said it yourself. I'm strong. And I will remind you. I'm smart. I'm smart enough to stay safe. I'm smart enough to ask for help.�\r      The man�s face transformed, fear overtaking him. Barty�s eyes had begun to glow bright white, as if something inside of him had lit ablaze.\r      �Andrew, I can fix this if you tell me what you did.� The boy�s voice had also begun changing. It sounded deeper, fuller, as if another spoke through him. �Who is Melora Freedman?� \r      The man backed away, fear covering him as fully as the water in which he died. �She�s a girl that died when I was in school,� he gagged, holding his stomach. \r      Batty stood straight, emotionless. �How did you know her?�\r      �I can�t,� Andrew replied.\r      �You can,� Barty commanded. �Tell me now before it's too late!�\r      �I can�t, Barty! I won't!� The man�s voice rose, breaking through the pain. �I swore!�\r      �Andrew Beauregard,� Barty spoke, growing tall and dark. �Tell me what you did.�\r      The father shrank, curling up against the wall. He shook uncontrollably as his body seemed to twist and shrivel. Then, his face morphed into a thin, skull-like figure with eyes dead and dark. �I�� he breathed a deep breath, preparing to scream, �SWOOOORE!� He let out the final word like a battlecry, a demon�s roar. The room shook, and the moonlight came upon him, revealing skin, bruised and riddled with thick purple veins.\r      Barty, face dark and menacing, looked upon him with supernatural eyes, shining in the darkness. Then, he shrunk, returning to his normal appearance, the look of a boy helpless before oncoming doom.\r      A train whistle echoed in the night air, breaking the silence of the moment. Both recognized how quiet the room had been. Now, the low rumbling rhythm of the train could be heard. Then, breathless and helpless, Andrew Beauregard broke the stillness with a whisper of a voice. �I have to go.� He struggled for breath. �Will you go with me to the train? I can't leave without you.�\r      Barty studied him. His appearance had become soft again, masking the demon inside. Whatever lay under the surface had been more devastating than anything Barty knew about the man.\r      �I will go with you. But I don't where.� Tears again fell down his cheeks. �Do you have to go?�\r      The man leaned forward into a crawl, grasping for the desk. He pulled himself up and limped to the other side of the room. �I don�t know either, Barty. All I know is I hurt. I can't exist like this anymore. I want to find your mom. I want to feel better. I need to go on. I just had to see you one more time.�\r      Barry wiped his face with his shoulder. He swallowed, accepting the situation. �Why now? Why wait? You knew I could see. You let me think I was crazy.�\r      The man looked down at the shelf that held the yearbook. �I�ve been here, Barty. The whole time. You've been too good to disobey, to come in here. Something changed in you, and,� he paused, eyes locked on the yearbook. �I�m afraid.�\r      �Afraid of what?� Barty questioned.\r      �Afraid of what you will become. It�s in your blood.�\r      He looked at Barty again, desperate and afraid. �In that book, you're going to learn things that I can't say out loud. Just know I love you. I hope you don�t hate me. I hope you forgive me.� Barry nodded agreement.\r      He took his fathers hand and quietly led him out. They walked through the living room, where Sarah had passed out on the red couch, the TV still running episodes of an old black and white program. Then, quietly, Barty opened the front door and stepped out into the night, still holding his father�s ghostly hand. A soft breeze welcomed him into the wilderness of the dark.\r      When they walked, the elder Beauregard leaned against the boy for support. The man lowered himself down the stair of the porch, grasping at the wooden column to steady himself.\r      �Why can I touch you?� Barty asked. He had wondered this for some time.\r      �Probably for the same reason you can see me,� replied his father. \r      This felt like less of an answer and more of an observation. �But why? Why can I see you at all?�\r      His father thought for a moment as they hobbled down the driveway together. They turned right on the street in the direction of the dead end. �I don�t really know. Your grandfather, Lucious, will know more about it.�\r      They walked in silence, under the orange lamplight that bathed only a few spots on the road. The houses slept silently on the sides of the street, like  giants. Barty hoped not to disturb them or draw attention. He wondered how odd it might appear to his neighbors that he would be walking alone at night toward the Trail.\r      In front of them, like a siren�s song, the train grew louder, filling the atmosphere with thumping. They reached the place where the asphalt ended and transitioned to weeds, leaves, and trees. But through the clearing, the place where Barty and his neighbors pushed through to the Trail, black shadows shifted and glimmered, speeding past the trees. It was the train.\r      The chugging had grown so loud now that Barty immediately resisted the urge to cover his ears. He could not while he still supported his father. Together, they hiked down through the dip in the wood, through the trees. Then, Barty could see it.\r      As far as he could see in both directions, the train stretched on, with boxcars and passenger cars whizzing past. The passenger sections glowed from within with warm light through round windows. The light from these hit Barty in the face repeatedly as it alternated with shadows.\r      At once, a dark wonder took hold of the boy and he felt afraid. It seemed like a new world had opened for him, a world of demons and ghosts and magic and� death. In this world, Barty�s father lived, or rather, lingered. It was the world in which his father would depart, where Barty himself might not visit until the end.\r      �I love you, son,� Andrew Beauregard shouted over the sound of the train. He looked down at the boy, his face shriveled in grief.\r      Barty looked at him in the face and loved him. He had bags under his eyes and dirt on his cheeks, but still, he remained his father, the man that had single handedly carved a path forward for them. This man comforted him through sickness and provided for him. This man had been his rock and protector for thirteen years. In the end, Barty realized that this man needed protecting himself, and no one had done it.\r      �I love you,� Barty replied, though he did not shout. He could hardly speak. \r      His father nodded and walked forward to where the train met the grass. He held out his hand and raised his thumb. Barty flinched as parts of the train came flying by the man�s head. How silly, he thought. He�s dead.\r      Then, as if in response, some devilish hand reached out of a boxcar and met Andrew Beauregard�s in the air. It grabbed him furiously, yanking the ghost and pulling him into the container like a rag doll.\r      Barty could no longer see him. He stood there and watched the train, knowing that no train had run in St. Fischer Parish for more than several decades. \r      When finally the train disappeared, and Barty had done all the crying he could, he walked back to his home, opened the door, and went to bed. He knew the yearbook waited to be read, studied, and investigated. Not tonight, he said to himself. Not tonight.",
