        "text": "CHAPTER TEN\rMont Linola Junior Highschool, 2000\r      �So, I�ve been thinking,� Kelly Prescott said.\r      She caught Barty as he began his daily ascent up the steps of Mont Linola Junior High. Not now, he thought. The last thing Barty needed was another joke from Kelly Prescott. He continued walking forward, pretending to not see her.\r      �Barty!� she said a little louder. �Barty Beauregard!�\r      Barty stopped moving and closed his eyes. �What, Kelly?�\r      �I�ve been thinking,� she began again.\r      You could have fooled me, Barty thought.\r      �In light of everything going on with our situation,� she continued.\r      �Our situation?� Barty repeated. �You mean the situation with my dad?�\r      �Exactly,� she replied. �I mean with the fact that we�re family and all. And the fact that your dad just died��\r      Barty knew where this would end. �I get it, Kelly. I really do. Don�t even worry about it.� He hated the idea of hearing the words out loud. Talking felt like a burden. In fact, listening seemed like too much effort.\r      �It would just seem so weird if��\r      �We went to the dance together,� Barty interrupted. �I get it.� He continued walking forward, the conversation finished.\r      Her cheeks turned as pink as her bow. �No!� She burst this out. Then, cutting him off mid-walk, she stood directly in front of him.\r      �Move, Kelly.� Barty had had enough.\r      �No, Barty. If you think I�m going to break it off with the loser kid, especially after his dad just dies, you�re dumber than a bag of bricks, Barty Beauregard! Especially if we�re family. Cousins go to dances together all the time!�\r      Too stunned to speak, his face froze. How could she think this a good time to drop this on him? How could she be this obtuse? A million thoughts swam to the surface of his mind, most of them wildly inappropriate.\r      �KELLY!� Barty shouted this, and when the echo returned to his ears, every eye had turned to watch. �I�m not going to the dance with you! I was NEVER going to go with you! I just didn�t know how to get out of it. But I know now. This is it. Leave me alone!�\r      She froze. Instead of pink, her face now looked a dark shade of red. She stayed stuck like this for almost a minute before Barty said anything again.\r      �Get it?� Barty demanded.\r      An individual tear started down her face. Then, when she could finally speak, she bit her lip and growled. �Fine,� she said, slightly whimpering between words. �If this is how you want to do it, I can do it as well.� With a loud bark of a shout, she grabbed his shirt and shoved him backward. \r      Unable to react, he fell onto his back, flattening his backpack. Before he could rise, a loud scream trailed over his head like a battle cry. Black basketball sneakers launched over him. \r      �You�� Mildred screamed a nasty name and threw herself at Kelly�s exiting body, thrusting the girl to the ground by the bow in her hair.\r      Barty sat up in time to watch Kelly realize what hit her. She turned over and crawled to her feet as the Preppy Pinks quickly ran to help. �I�m fine!� She shrieked, straightening her hair. �Let me punch the witch that touched me!�\r      Mildred stood directly in her line of sight, glaring menacingly. She held out her fists, looking rather ridiculous. Kelly recoiled, afraid to advance. Mildred stepped forward, invading Kelly�s space. �Touch my friend again, and I�ll rip your hair out.�\r      �Detention!� A voice shouted out over the crowded students in the hall. �Detention for all of you!� Coach Grant tore through the kids, speedwalking like an Olympian.\r      �Coach!� Mildred cried. �She attacked him. You had to see that!�\r      Barty, still on the ground, felt his head beginning to heat. A crowd had simultaneously paused to watch. Red-faced, Kelly rushed forward to plead her case. �I didn�t touch the dweeb!�\r      The two began going back and forth, steadily growing louder until they might have thrown blows again. Coach Grant, in his squealy voice, began yelling over them. �Alright, alright. ALRIGHT! I said STOP!� The two girls, steam drifting off their skin, glared into each other�s eyes.\r      �I don�t care who started it! You all get detention. After school.� He looked around at the scene that they had created. He looked even angrier, which looked silly on his frail body. �Break it up! Go to class! Shew!� Then, he marched away, as Mildred and Kelly mouthed curse words at each other and collected their things.\r      Barty began walking to class without speaking to Mildred. She quickly shuffled to catch up to him, but he did not acknowledge her. �Barty, I�m sorry.�\r      He glanced in her direction, still stepping. �I don�t care. Forget it.�\r      She followed closely behind, trying to match his urgency. �What happened yesterday?�\r      �I can�t say everything now,� he replied. �Let�s talk at lunch.�\r      �See you then,� she said before parting ways.\r\r\t\r      \r      \r      2\r      \r      \r      \r      \r      \r      Cory Gilford - Barty Beauregard and the Fabulous Fraud - 1",
